{"title_page": "Axis mundi", "text_new": "{{short description|The world center in some religions or philosophies, connection between Heaven and Earth}}\n{{Redirect|Navel of the World}}\n{{about|the connection|the album|Axis Mundi (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{synthesis|date=December 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Hindukailash.JPG|thumb|right|[[Mount Kailash]], depicting the holy family: [[Shiva]] and [[Parvati]], cradling [[Murugan|Skanda]] with [[Ganesha]] by Shiva's side]]\nIn [[astronomy]],  '''axis mundi''' is the Latin term for the [[Earth axis]] (the [[celestial pole]]).\nIn a geocentric coordinate system, this is the [[axis of rotation]] of the [[celestial sphere]]. \nConsequently, in ancient [[Greco-Roman astronomy]], the ''axis mundi'' is the axis of rotation of the [[celestial spheres|planetary spheres]] of the classical [[Geocentrism|geocentric]] model of the cosmos.<ref>the term{{cn|date=December 2019}}<!--cite the Greek term--> is used by [[Geminus]] in his ''Elementa'', in early modern editions misattributed to [[Proclus]] as ''Commentarius in sphaeram''. R.B. Todd, 'The Manuscripts of the Pseudo-Proclan Sphaera', ''Revue d'histoire des textes'' 23 (1993), 57-71.\n<!-- better citation, establish the original Greek term\nR. B. Todd, 'Geminus, Ps.-Proclan Sphaera', V. Brown (ed.), Catalogus Translationum et Commentariorum: Medieval and Renaissance Latin Translations and Commentaries, Annotated List and Guides, vol. VIII (Washington DC, 2003), pp.24-48.-->\nThe term continues to be used in modern astronomical works throughout the 18th century, e.g.  [[Johann Samuel Traugott Gehler]], ''Physikalisches W\u00f6rterbuch'' (1791), [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_5qEtAAAAcAAJ/page/n701 p. 688].</ref>\n\nIn 20th-century [[comparative mythology]], the term '''axis mundi''' (variously also{{huh|date=December 2019}}  '''cosmic axis''', '''world axis''', '''world pillar''', '''center of the world''', '''world tree''') was greatly extended to refer to any mythological concept representing \"the connection between [[Heaven]] and [[Earth]]\" or the \"higher and lower realms\".<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.48-51</ref>\nThe concept was introduced by [[Mircea Eliade]] in the 1950s.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.40</ref> It is closely related to the mythological concept of ''[[omphalos]]'' (navel) of the world or cosmos.<ref>J. C. Cooper. ''An Illustrated Encyclopedia of Traditional Symbols.'' Thames and Hudson: New York, 1978. {{ISBN|0500271259}}.</ref><ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Willard Trask). 'Archetypes and Repetition' in ''The Myth of the Eternal Return. Princeton, 1971. {{ISBN|0691017778}}. p.16</ref><ref>Winther, Rasmus Gr\u00f8nfeldt (2014) World Navels. ''Cartouche'' 89: 15\u201321 https://www.academia.edu/8727362/World_Navels</ref>\nItems adduced as exampes of the ''axis mundi'' by comparative mythologists include plants (notably a [[tree]] but also other types of plants such as a [[vine]] or [[Plant stem|stalk]]), a [[world mountain|mountain]],  a column of [[smoke]] or [[fire]], or a product of human manufacture (such as a staff, a [[tower]], a [[ladder]], a [[staircase]], a [[maypole]], a [[cross]], a [[steeple (architecture)|steeple]], a [[rope]], a [[totem pole]], a [[Column|pillar]], a [[spire]]). \nIts proximity to heaven may carry implications that are chiefly religious ([[pagoda]], [[temple mount]], [[minaret]], [[church (building)|church]]) or secular ([[obelisk]], [[lighthouse]], [[rocket]], [[skyscraper]]). The image appears in religious and secular contexts.<ref name=\"Alain Gheerbrandt 1982. pp.61-63\">[[Jean Chevalier (writer)|Jean Chevalier]] and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.61\u201363, 173\u2013175</ref> The ''axis mundi'' symbol may be found in cultures utilizing [[shamanism|shamanic]] practices or [[animism|animist]] belief systems, in major world religions, and in technologically advanced \"urban centers\". In [[Mircea Eliade]]'s opinion, \"Every Microcosm, every inhabited region, has a Centre; that is to say, a place that is sacred above all.\"<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1991. p.39\">Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.39</ref> The axis mundi is often associated with [[mandalas]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:FujiSunriseKawaguchiko2025WP.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Mount Fuji]], [[Japan]]]]\nThe symbol originates in a natural and universal psychological perception: that the spot one occupies stands at \"the center of the world\". This space serves as a microcosm of order because it is known and settled. Outside the boundaries of the microcosm lie foreign realms that, because they are unfamiliar or not ordered, represent chaos, death or night.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.37-39</ref> From the center one may still venture in any of the four cardinal directions, make discoveries, and establish new centers as new realms become known and settled. The name of [[China]], meaning \"Middle Nation\" ({{lang|zh|\u4e2d\u56fd}} [[pinyin]]: ''{{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}''), is often interpreted as an expression of an ancient perception that the Chinese polity (or group of polities) occupied the center of the world, with other lands lying in various directions relative to it.<ref name=\"Alain Gheerbrandt 1982. pp.61-63\"/>\n\nWithin the central known universe a specific locale-often a mountain or other elevated place, a spot where earth and sky come closest gains status as center of the center, the '''axis mundi'''. High mountains are typically regarded as sacred by peoples living near them. Shrines are often erected at the summit or base.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.41-43</ref> [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Mount Kunlun]] fills a similar role in China.<ref>Wang, Chong. ''Lunheng Part I: Philosophical Essays of Wang Ch'ung''. Trans. Alfred Forke. London: Luzac & Co., 1907. p.337.</ref> For the ancient Hebrews [[Mount Zion]] expressed the symbol.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} [[Sioux]] beliefs take the [[Black Hills]] as the axis mundi.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} [[Mount Kailash]] is holy to [[Hinduism]] and several religions in [[Tibet]]. The [[Pitjantjatjara people|Pitjantjatjara]] people in central Australia consider [[Uluru]] to be central to both their world and culture. In ancient [[Mesopotamia]] the cultures of ancient [[Sumer]] and [[Babylon]] erected artificial mountains, or [[ziggurat]]s, on the flat river plain. These supported staircases leading to temples at the top. The Hindu temples in India are often situated on high mountains. E.g. [[Amarnath Temple|Amarnath]], [[Tirumala Venkateswara Temple|Tirupati]], [[Vaishno Devi]] etc. The pre-Columbian residents of [[Teotihuac\u00e1n]] in [[Mexico]] erected huge [[pyramid]]s featuring staircases leading to heaven. These [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Amerindian]] temples were often placed on top of caves or subterranean springs, which were thought to be openings to the underworld.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Art of Colonial Latin America|last=Bailey|first=Gauvin Alexander|publisher=Phaidon Press Limited|year=2005|location=New York (NY)|pages=21}}</ref> [[Jacob's Ladder]] is an axis mundi image, as is the [[Temple Mount]]. For Christians the [[Cross]] on Mount [[Calvary]] expresses the symbol.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.680\u2013685</ref> The Middle Kingdom, China, had a central mountain, [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun]], known in [[Taoism|Taoist literature]] as \"the mountain at the middle of the world.\" To \"go into the mountains\" meant to dedicate oneself to a spiritual life.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.681</ref> Monasteries of all faiths tend, like shrines, to be placed at elevated spots. Wise religious teachers are typically depicted in literature and art as bringing their revelations at world centers: mountains, trees, temples.\n\nBecause the axis mundi is an idea that unites a number of concrete images, no contradiction exists in regarding multiple spots as \"the center of the world\". The symbol can operate in a number of locales at once.<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1991. p.39\"/> [[Mount Hermon]] was regarded as the axis mundi in [[Canaan|Canaanite]] tradition, from where the sons of God are introduced descending in [[1 Enoch]] (1En6:6).<ref name=\"Bautch2003\">{{cite book|author=Kelley Coblentz Bautch|title=A Study of the Geography of 1 Enoch 17\u201319: \"no One Has Seen what I Have Seen\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3FPNFEtWNrQC&pg=PA62|date=25 September 2003|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-13103-3|page=62}}</ref> The [[Urartu|ancient Armenians]] had a number of holy sites, the most important of which was [[Mount Ararat]], which was thought to be the home of the gods as well as the center of the Universe.<ref>http://www.peopleofar.com/2013/08/11/noahs-ark-in-the-mountains-of-armenia/</ref> Likewise, the [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]] regarded several sites as places of earth's ''[[omphalos]]'' (navel) stone, notably the oracle at [[Delphi]], while still maintaining a belief in a cosmic [[world tree]] and in [[Mount Olympus]] as the abode of the gods. Judaism has the [[Temple Mount]], Christianity has the [[Mount of Olives]] and [[Calvary]], Islam has the [[Ka'aba]], said to be the first building on earth, and the [[Temple Mount]] ([[Dome of the Rock]]).  In [[Hinduism]], [[Mount Kailash]] is identified with the mythical [[Mount Meru]] and regarded as the home of [[Shiva]]; in [[Vajrayana Buddhism]], Mount Kailash is recognized as the most sacred place where all the [[Ley line|dragon currents]] converge and is regarded as the gateway to [[Shambhala]].  In [[Shinto]], the [[Ise Shrine]] is the omphalos.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}  In addition to the [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun Mountains]], where it is believed the [[peach tree of immortality]] is located, the [[Chinese folk religion]] recognizes four other specific mountains as pillars of the world.\n\nSacred places constitute world centers ([[omphalos]]) with the [[altar]] or place of prayer as the axis. Altars, incense sticks, candles and torches form the axis by sending a column of smoke, and prayer, toward heaven. The architecture of sacred places often reflects this role. \"Every temple or palace\u2014and by extension, every sacred city or royal residence\u2014is a Sacred Mountain, thus becoming a Centre.\"<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1971. p.12\">Mircea Eliade (tr. Willard Trask). 'Archetypes and Repetition' in ''The Myth of the Eternal Return. Princeton, 1971. {{ISBN|0691017778}}. p.12</ref> The [[stupa]] of [[Hinduism]], and later [[Buddhism]], reflects [[Mount Meru]]. Cathedrals are laid out in the form of a [[cross]], with the vertical bar representing the union of earth and heaven as the horizontal bars represent union of people to one another, with the altar at the intersection. [[Pagoda]] structures in Asian temples take the form of a stairway linking earth and heaven. A [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] in a church or a [[minaret]] in a mosque also serve as connections of earth and heaven. Structures such as the [[maypole]], derived from the [[Saxons]]' [[Irminsul]], and the [[totem pole]] among [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]] also represent world axes. The [[calumet (pipe)|calumet]], or sacred pipe, represents a column of smoke (the soul) rising form a world center.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.148\u2013149</ref> A [[mandala]] creates a world center within the boundaries of its two-dimensional space analogous to that created in three-dimensional space by a shrine.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.52-54</ref>\n\nIn the [[Classical element]]s and the Vedic [[Pancha Bhoota]] the axis mundi corresponds to [[Aether (mythology)|Aether]], the quintessence.\n\n[[File:yggdrasil.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Yggdrasil]], the World Ash in Norse myths]]\n\n===Plants===\nPlants often serve as images of the axis mundi. The image of the [[Cosmic Tree]] provides an axis symbol that unites three planes: sky (branches), earth (trunk) and underworld (roots).<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.42-45</ref> In some [[Pacific island]] cultures the [[banyan]] tree, of which the [[Bodhi tree]] is of the [[Sacred Fig]] variety, is the abode of ancestor spirits. In Hindu religion, the banyan tree is considered sacred and is called ''ashwath vriksha'' (\"I am banyan tree among trees\" \u2013 ''[[Bhagavad Gita]]''). It represents eternal life because of its seemingly ever-expanding branches.  The Bodhi tree is also the name given to the tree under which [[Gautama Siddhartha]], the historical [[Buddhahood|Buddha]], sat on the night he attained [[Bodhi|enlightenment]]. The [[Mesoamerican world tree]] connects the planes of the Underworld and the sky with that of the terrestrial realm.<ref>{{cite book |author=Miller, Mary |authorlink=Mary Miller (art historian) |author2=Karl Taube |year=1993 |title=The Gods and Symbols of Ancient Mexico and the Maya |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |page=[https://archive.org/details/godssymbolsofa00mill/page/186 186] |isbn=0500050686 |url=https://archive.org/details/godssymbolsofa00mill/page/186 |author2-link=Karl Taube }}</ref> The [[Yggdrasil]], or World Ash, functions in much the same way in [[Norse mythology]]; it is the site where [[Odin]] found enlightenment. Other examples include [[Jievaras]] in [[Lithuanian mythology]] and [[Thor's Oak]] in the myths of the pre-Christian [[Germanic peoples]]. The [[Tree of Life]] and the [[Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil]] in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] present two aspects of the same image. Each is said to stand at the center of the [[Garden of Eden|Paradise garden]] from which four rivers flow to nourish the whole world. Each tree confers a boon. [[Bamboo]], the plant from which Asian calligraphy pens are made, represents knowledge and is regularly found on Asian college campuses. The [[Christmas tree]], which can be traced in its origins back to pre-Christian [[Europe]]an beliefs, represents an axis mundi.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Chevalier, Jean and Gheerbrandt, Alain. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.1025\u20131033</ref> {{clarify span|[[Entheogen]]s (psychoactive substances) are often regarded as world axes|date=November 2012}}, such as the [[Fly Agaric]] mushroom among the [[Evenks]] of [[Russia]].{{citation needed|date=November 2012}} In China, traditional cosmography sometimes depicts the world center marked with the Jian tree ({{lang|zh|\u5efa\u6728}}). Two more trees are placed at the East and West, corresponding to the points of sunrise and sunset, as described in the ''[[Huainanzi]]''.\n\n[[File:Da Vinci Vitruve Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[Vitruvian Man]]'' by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] (c. 1492)]]\n\n===Human figure===\nThe human body can express the symbol of world axis.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.54</ref> Some of the more abstract Tree of Life representations, such as the ''[[sefirot]]'' in [[Kabbalism]] and in the ''[[chakra]]'' system recognized by Hinduism and Buddhism, merge with the concept of the human body as a pillar between heaven and earth. Disciplines such as [[yoga]] and [[tai chi]] begin from the premise of the human body as axis mundi. The Buddha represents a world centre in human form.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Indian Symbolisms of Time and Eternity' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.76</ref> Large statues of a meditating figure unite the human figure with the symbolism of temple and tower. [[Astrology]] in all its forms assumes a connection between human health and affairs and the orientation of these with celestial bodies. World religions regard the body itself as a temple and prayer as a column uniting earth to heaven. The ancient [[Colossus of Rhodes]] combined the role of human figure with those of portal and skyscraper. The image of a human being suspended on a tree or a cross locates the figure at the axis where heaven and earth meet. The Renaissance image known as the [[Vitruvian Man]] represented a symbolic and mathematical exploration of the human form as world axis.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Homes===\nHomes can represent world centers. The symbolism for their residents is the same as for inhabitants of palaces and other sacred mountains.<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1971. p.12\"/> The hearth participates in the symbolism of the [[altar]] and a central [[garden]] participates in the symbolism of primordial [[Garden of Eden|paradise]]. In Asian cultures houses were traditionally laid out in the form of a square oriented toward the four compass directions. A traditional Asian home was oriented toward the sky through [[feng shui]], a system of [[geomancy]], just as a palace would be. Traditional Arab houses are also laid out as a square surrounding a central fountain that evokes a primordial garden paradise. Mircea Eliade noted that \"the symbolism of the pillar in [European] peasant houses likewise derives from the 'symbolic field' of the ''axis mundi''. In many archaic dwellings the central pillar does in fact serve as a means of communication with the heavens, with the sky.\"<ref>Mircea Eliade. 'Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i and Mythology' in ''Symbolism, the Sacred, and the Arts. Continuum, 1992. {{ISBN|0826406181}}. p. 100</ref> The nomadic peoples of Mongolia and the Americas more often lived in circular structures. The central pole of the tent still operated as an axis but a fixed reference to the four compass points was avoided.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.529\u2013531</ref>\n\n[[File:Caduceus large.jpg|thumb|110px|right|The [[caduceus]]]]\n\n===Shamanic function===\nA common [[shamanism|shamanic]] concept, and a universally told story, is that of the healer traversing the axis mundi to bring back knowledge from the other world. It may be seen in the stories from [[Odin]] and the [[Yggdrasil|World Ash Tree]] to [[the Garden of Eden]] and [[Jacob's Ladder]] to [[Jack and the Beanstalk]] and [[Rapunzel]]. It is the essence of the journey described in ''[[The Divine Comedy]]'' by [[Dante Alighieri]]. The epic poem relates its hero's descent and ascent through a series of spiral structures that take him from through the core of the earth, from the depths of Hell to celestial Paradise.\nIt is also a central tenet in the [[Southeastern Ceremonial Complex]].<ref>{{cite book |  last = Townsend | first = Richard F. |  title = Hero, Hawk, and Open Hand| publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | year = 2004 |  isbn = 0-300-10601-7| title-link = Hero, Hawk, and Open Hand }}</ref>\n\nAnyone or anything suspended on the axis between heaven and earth becomes a repository of potential knowledge. A special status accrues to the thing suspended: a [[Serpent (symbolism)|serpent]], a victim of crucifixion or hanging, a rod, a fruit, [[mistletoe]]. Derivations of this idea find form in the [[Rod of Asclepius]], an emblem of the medical profession, and in the [[caduceus]], an emblem of correspondence and commercial professions. The staff in these emblems represents the axis mundi while the [[Serpent (symbolism)|serpents]] act as guardians of, or guides to, knowledge.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.142\u2013145</ref>\n\n==Traditional expressions==\n\n===Asia===\n*[[Wuji (philosophy)|Wuji]]\n*[[Bodhi tree]], especially where [[Gautama Buddha]] found Enlightenment\n*[[Eight Pillars]]: eight axes mundi in Chinese mythology\n*[[Pagoda]]\n*[[Stupa]] in Buddhism\n*[[Mount Meru (mythology)|Mount Meru]] in Hinduism and Buddhism\n*[[Mount Kailash]] regarded by Hinduism and several religions in [[Tibet]], e.g. [[B\u00f6n]]\n*[[Jambudvipa]] in [[Hinduism]] and [[Jainism]] which is regarded as the actual navel of the [[Jain cosmology|universe]] (which is human in form)\n*[[Kailasa]] (India), the abode of [[Shiva]]\n*[[Mount Mandara|Mandara]] (India)\n*[[Shiva Lingam]] (India)\n*[[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun Mountain]] (China), residence of the Immortals and the site of [[Peaches of Immortality|a peach tree offering immortality]]\n*Human figure ([[yoga]], [[taiji|tai chi]], [[Buddha]] in [[meditation]], [[religious image|sacred images]] or [[icon]])\n* [[Ise Shrine]] ([[Shinto]])\n* Central courtyard in traditional home\n*[[Bamboo|Bamboo stalk]], associated with knowledge and learning\n*Mago Stronghold (Old Korea) also known as Mago-seong, Mago San-seong, Go-Seong, Halmi-seong. Primordial Home of the Great Goddess and her primordial descendants<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Mago Way: Re-discovering Mago, the Great Goddess from East Asia|last=Hwang|first=Helen Hye-Sook|publisher=Mago Books|year=2015|isbn=9781516907922|pages=136\u2013142}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\n*[[Garden of Eden]] with four rivers\n*[[Tree of Life]] and [[Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil]]\n*[[Mountains of Ararat|Mt. Ararat]] landing place of Noah's ark \n*[[Ziggurat]], or [[Tower of Babel]]\n*[[Jacob's Ladder]]\n*[[Jerusalem]], specifically, the [[Temple in Jerusalem|Holy Temple]]; focus of Jewish prayer where Abraham bound Isaac\n*[[Christian Cross|Cross of the Crucifixion]]\n*[[Steeple (architecture)|Steeple]]\n*[[Ka'aba]] in [[Mecca]]; focus of Muslim prayer\n*[[Qutb]], In Sufism, an intermediary figure between God and mankind\n*[[Dome of the Rock]] where [[Muhammad]], in Islam, is believed to have ascended to heaven\n*[[Minaret]]\n*[[Dilmun]]\n*[[Garizim]] (Samaria)\n*[[Hara Berezaiti]] (Persia)\n*[[Zaphon]]\n*[[Mount Qaf]]\n*[[Mount Carmel]]<ref>{{citation|last=Akerdahl|first=Per-Olof|date=2000|url=https://bahai-library.com/akerdahl_pilgrimage_religious_identity|chapter=Pilgrimage and Religious Identity in the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith|title=Lights of Irfan|publisher=Irfan Colloquia|location=Wilmette, IL|volume=1|pages=1-20}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n*[[Meskel]] bonfire\n*[[Stelae]] of the [[Aksumite Empire]]\n*[[Pyramids]] of [[Egypt]]\n*[[Osun-Osogbo]] Sacred Grove of [[Nigeria]]\n*[[Jebel Barkal]] of [[Sudan]]\n*[[Idafe Rock]] of [[Guanches|prehispanic]] [[La Palma]]\n*[[Mt Kenya]] of [[Kenya]]\n*[[Mount Kilimanjaro]]\n\n===Europe===\n*[[Yggdrasil]] (the world ash-tree in [[Norse cosmology]])\n*[[Irminsul]] (the great pillar in [[Germanic paganism]])\n*[[Hill of Uisneach]] (the navel and center of Ireland in [[Irish mythology]])<ref>Alwyn and Brinley Rees. ''Celtic Heritage''. Thames and Hudson: New York, 1961. {{ISBN|0500270392}}. pp. 159\u2013161.</ref>\n*[[Mount Olympus]] in Greece, court of the gods ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Sampo]] or Sammas ([[Finnic mythology|Baltic-Finnic mythology]])\n*[[Delphi]], home of the Oracle of Delphi ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Colossus of Rhodes]] ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Maypole]] ([[East Europe]] and [[Germanic paganism]])\n*[[Purgatorio]], [[Dante]]'s vision of Purgatory as a mountain ([[Christian poetry]])\n*[[Jack and the Beanstalk|Jack's Beanstalk]] ([[England|English]] [[fairy tale]])\n*[[Rapunzel|Rapunzel's Tower]] ([[Germany|German]] fairy tale)\n*[[Hearth]]\n*Central pillar of peasant homes\n*[[Altar]]\n*[[Vitruvian Man]]\n*[[Hagia Sophia]]\n*[[St. Peter's Basilica]]\n*[[Umbilicus urbis Romae]], a structure in the [[Roman Forum]] from where all the [[Roman road]]s parted.\n*[[Isle of Man]] ([[Emain Ablach]], the gate to the Otherworld in Irish Mythology)\n\n===The Americas===\n* Julia's Hamok under Haiwana\n*[[Teotihuac\u00e1n|Teotihuac\u00e1n Pyramids]]\n*[[Totem Pole]]\n*[[Rehue]]\n*[[Potomitan]]\n*[[Tent]]\n*[[Black Hills]] ([[Sioux]])\n*[[Calumet (pipe)|Calumet]] (sacred pipe)\n*[[Sipapu]] ([[Hopi]])\n*[[Southeastern Ceremonial Complex]]\n*[[Medicine wheel]]s of the northern [[Great Plains]]\n*[[Temple Lot]] ([[Mormonism]])\n*[[Cuzco]] ([[Incas]]), meaning \"navel\" in [[Quechua languages|Quechua]]{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n*[[Chakana]]\n*[[Mesoamerican world tree]]\n*[[Lanzon]]\n*[[Turtle Island (North America)|Turtle Island]]\n*[[Yvy marae]], the sacred land \"free from all evil\", whose pursuit led to the colonization of lowland South America by the [[Tup\u00ed people|Tup\u00ed]] and [[Guaran\u00ed people|Guaran\u00ed]] peoples, guided by the [[karai (Tup\u00ed-Guaran\u00ed culture)|karai]] or priests<ref>CASCUDO, L. C. ''Geografia dos mitos brasileiros. ''3\u00aa edi\u00e7\u00e3o. S\u00e3o Paulo. Global. 2002. p. 133.</ref><ref>CLASTRES, P. ''Le grand parler''. Paris: \u00c9ditions du seuil, '975. p. 9</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tekoamboytyitarypu.site90.com/index.php?news&nid=9 |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000659/http://www.tekoamboytyitarypu.site90.com/index.php?news&nid=9 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Sul\u00e1yom]] in [[Talamancan mythology]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Diccionario de mitolog\u00eda bribri|last=Jara, Carla Victoria, 1961\u2013|date=2003|publisher=Editorial de la Universidad de Costa Rica|others=Garc\u00eda Segura, Al\u00ed.|isbn=9977677387|edition=1|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|pages=196\u2013197|language=Spanish|oclc=53238389}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n*[[Uluru]]\n*[[Rainbow Serpent|Rainbow Snake]]\n\n==Modern expressions==\n{{see also|North\u2013South divide|East\u2013West dichotomy}}\n[[File:101.tall.altonthompson.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Taipei 101]] ([[Taiwan]])]]\n{{Synthesis|date=November 2008}}\nAxis mundi symbolism continues to be evoked, even in modern societies, through various art forms and has a deep rooted spiritual inspiration that transcends time.\n\nThe idea has proven consequential in the realm of [[architecture]].  Structures that have a spiritual meaning, that inspire and create a connection between the spiritual world and the physical world, that are erected as monuments to commemorate are achievements can be considered to be inspired by the axis mundi. The pyramids that have been erected throughout human history serve as perfect examples of axis mundi.  A [[skyscraper]], as the term itself suggests, suggests the connection of earth and sky, as do [[spire]] structures of all sorts. Such buildings come to be regarded as \"centers\" of an inhabited area, or even the world, and serve as icons of its ideals.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. p.137</ref> The first skyscraper of modern times, the [[Eiffel Tower]], exemplifies this role. The structure was erected in 1889 in [[Paris]], [[France]], to serve as the centerpiece for the [[Exposition Universelle (1889)|Exposition Universelle]], making it a symbolic world center from the planning stages. It has served as an iconic image for the city and the nation ever since.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. p. 19</ref> Landmark skyscrapers often take names that clearly identify them as centers.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. pp. 45, 69, 81, 91, 97,135, 136, 143</ref>\n\nArtistic representations of the axis mundi are plentiful. Just one example of these is the ''Colonne sans fin'' (''[[The Endless Column]]'', 1938) an abstract [[sculpture]] by Romanian [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]]. The column takes the form of a \"sky pillar\" ({{lang|ro|{{vanchor|columna cerului}}}}) upholding the heavens even as its rhythmically repeating segments invite climb and suggest the possibility of ascension.<ref>Mircea Eliade. 'Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i and Mythology' in ''Symbolism, the Sacred, and the Arts. Continuum, 1992. {{ISBN|0826406181}}. p.99-100</ref>\n\nVisual representation of the axis mundi in contemporary art is currently being achieved by photographer Jennifer Westjohn.  By the process of mirror symmetry of a single photograph the artist exposes an entirely new image: the 5th point.  The viewer is then introduced to a coalescing of nature and the universe which lends new perspective to the original image.  This artistic representation of axis mundi opens the mind up to a new visual dimension both energistic and shamanic.<ref>Jennifer Westjohn. Photographer. \"jenniferwestjohn.com\" \"the5thpoint.com\" 2013\u20132017</ref>\n\nAxis mundi symbolism exists in modern [[Spaceflight|space travel]].<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp. 18, 1020\u20131022</ref> Each astronaut embarks on a perilous journey into the heavens, per se, and if successful, returns with a boon for dissemination. The [[Apollo 13]] insignia stated it succinctly: ''Ex luna scientia'' (\"From the Moon, knowledge\").<ref>[http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/history/apollo/apollo-13/apollo-13.html Nasa Apollo Mission: Apollo 13. 2007-08-25]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Alchemy]]\n*[[Celestial sphere]]\n*[[Comparative mythology]]\n*[[Crucifix]]\n*[[Fertile Crescent]]\n*[[Fleur de lis]]\n*[[Herma]]\n*[[History of the center of the Universe]]\n*[[Hyperborea]]\n*[[North pole]]\n*[[Optical axis]]\n*[[Palmette]]\n*[[Phurba]]\n*[[Taiji (philosophy)]]\n*[[Vorticism]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|group=lungring}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Axis Mundi}}\n[[Category:Comparative mythology]]\n[[Category:Esoteric cosmology]]\n[[Category:Geographical centres]]\n[[Category:History of astrology]]\n[[Category:History of religion]]\n[[Category:Mythological cosmologies]]\n[[Category:Mythological places]]\n[[Category:Panentheism]]\n[[Category:Pantheism]]\n[[Category:Religious symbols]]\n[[Category:Shamanism]]\n[[Category:Spirituality]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|The world center in some religions or philosophies, connection between Heaven and Earth}}\n{{Redirect|Navel of the World}}\n{{about|the connection|the album|Axis Mundi (album)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{synthesis|date=December 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Hindukailash.JPG|thumb|right|[[Mount Kailash]], depicting the holy family: [[Shiva]] and [[Parvati]], cradling [[Murugan|Skanda]] with [[Ganesha]] by Shiva's side]]\nIn [[astronomy]],  '''axis mundi''' is the Latin term for the [[Earth axis]] (the [[celestial pole]]).\nIn a geocentric coordinate system, this is the [[axis of rotation]] of the [[celestial sphere]]. \nConsequently, in ancient [[Greco-Roman astronomy]], the ''axis mundi'' is the axis of rotation of the [[celestial spheres|planetary spheres]] of the classical [[Geocentrism|geocentric]] model of the cosmos.<ref>the term{{cn|date=December 2019}}<!--cite the Greek term--> is used by [[Geminus]] in his ''Elementa'', in early modern editions misattributed to [[Proclus]] as ''Commentarius in sphaeram''. R.B. Todd, 'The Manuscripts of the Pseudo-Proclan Sphaera', ''Revue d'histoire des textes'' 23 (1993), 57-71.\n<!-- better citation, establish the original Greek term\nR. B. Todd, 'Geminus, Ps.-Proclan Sphaera', V. Brown (ed.), Catalogus Translationum et Commentariorum: Medieval and Renaissance Latin Translations and Commentaries, Annotated List and Guides, vol. VIII (Washington DC, 2003), pp.24-48.-->\nThe term continues to be used in modern astronomical works throughout the 18th century, e.g.  [[Johann Samuel Traugott Gehler]], ''Physikalisches W\u00f6rterbuch'' (1791), [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_5qEtAAAAcAAJ/page/n701 p. 688].</ref>\n\nIn 20th-century [[comparative mythology]], the term '''axis mundi''' (variously also{{huh|date=December 2019}}  '''cosmic axis''', '''world axis''', '''world pillar''', '''center of the world''', '''world tree''') was greatly extended to refer to any mythological concept representing \"the connection between [[Heaven]] and [[Earth]]\" or the \"higher and lower realms\".<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.48-51</ref>\nThe concept was introduced by [[Mircea Eliade]] in the 1950s.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.40</ref> It is closely related to the mythological concept of ''[[omphalos]]'' (navel) of the world or cosmos.<ref>J. C. Cooper. ''An Illustrated Encyclopedia of Traditional Symbols.'' Thames and Hudson: New York, 1978. {{ISBN|0500271259}}.</ref><ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Willard Trask). 'Archetypes and Repetition' in ''The Myth of the Eternal Return. Princeton, 1971. {{ISBN|0691017778}}. p.16</ref><ref>Winther, Rasmus Gr\u00f8nfeldt (2014) World Navels. ''Cartouche'' 89: 15\u201321 https://www.academia.edu/8727362/World_Navels</ref>\nItems adduced as exampes of the ''axis mundi'' by comparative mythologists include plants (notably a [[tree]] but also other types of plants such as a [[vine]] or [[Plant stem|stalk]]), a [[world mountain|mountain]],  a column of [[smoke]] or [[fire]], or a product of human manufacture (such as a staff, a [[tower]], a [[ladder]], a [[staircase]], a [[maypole]], a [[cross]], a [[steeple (architecture)|steeple]], a [[rope]], a [[totem pole]], a [[Column|pillar]], a [[spire]]). \nIts proximity to heaven may carry implications that are chiefly religious ([[pagoda]], [[temple mount]], [[minaret]], [[church (building)|church]]) or secular ([[obelisk]], [[lighthouse]], [[rocket]], [[skyscraper]]). The image appears in religious and secular contexts.<ref name=\"Alain Gheerbrandt 1982. pp.61-63\">[[Jean Chevalier (writer)|Jean Chevalier]] and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.61\u201363, 173\u2013175</ref> The ''axis mundi'' symbol may be found in cultures utilizing [[shamanism|shamanic]] practices or [[animism|animist]] belief systems, in major world religions, and in technologically advanced \"urban centers\". In [[Mircea Eliade]]'s opinion, \"Every Microcosm, every inhabited region, has a Centre; that is to say, a place that is sacred above all.\"<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1991. p.39\">Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.39</ref> The axis mundi is often associated with [[mandalas]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:FujiSunriseKawaguchiko2025WP.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Mount Fuji]], [[Japan]]]]\nThe symbol originates in a natural and universal psychological perception: that the spot one occupies stands at \"the center of the world\". This space serves as a microcosm of order because it is known and settled. Outside the boundaries of the microcosm lie foreign realms that, because they are unfamiliar or not ordered, represent chaos, death or night.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.37-39</ref> From the center one may still venture in any of the four cardinal directions, make discoveries, and establish new centers as new realms become known and settled. The name of [[China]], meaning \"Middle Nation\" ({{lang|zh|\u4e2d\u56fd}} [[pinyin]]: ''{{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}''), is often interpreted as an expression of an ancient perception that the Chinese polity (or group of polities) occupied the center of the world, with other lands lying in various directions relative to it.<ref name=\"Alain Gheerbrandt 1982. pp.61-63\"/>\n\nWithin the central known universe a specific locale-often a mountain or other elevated place, a spot where earth and sky come closest gains status as center of the center, the '''axis mundi'''. High mountains are typically regarded as sacred by peoples living near them. Shrines are often erected at the summit or base.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.41-43</ref> [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Mount Kunlun]] fills a similar role in China.<ref>Wang, Chong. ''Lunheng Part I: Philosophical Essays of Wang Ch'ung''. Trans. Alfred Forke. London: Luzac & Co., 1907. p.337.</ref> For the ancient Hebrews [[Mount Zion]] expressed the symbol.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} [[Sioux]] beliefs take the [[Black Hills]] as the axis mundi.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} [[Mount Kailash]] is holy to [[Hinduism]] and several religions in [[Tibet]]. The [[Pitjantjatjara people|Pitjantjatjara]] people in central Australia consider [[Uluru]] to be central to both their world and culture. In ancient [[Mesopotamia]] the cultures of ancient [[Sumer]] and [[Babylon]] erected artificial mountains, or [[ziggurat]]s, on the flat river plain. These supported staircases leading to temples at the top. The Hindu temples in India are often situated on high mountains. E.g. [[Amarnath Temple|Amarnath]], [[Tirumala Venkateswara Temple|Tirupati]], [[Vaishno Devi]] etc. The pre-Columbian residents of [[Teotihuac\u00e1n]] in [[Mexico]] erected huge [[pyramid]]s featuring staircases leading to heaven. These [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Amerindian]] temples were often placed on top of caves or subterranean springs, which were thought to be openings to the underworld.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Art of Colonial Latin America|last=Bailey|first=Gauvin Alexander|publisher=Phaidon Press Limited|year=2005|location=New York (NY)|pages=21}}</ref> [[Jacob's Ladder]] is an axis mundi image, as is the [[Temple Mount]]. For Christians the [[Cross]] on Mount [[Calvary]] expresses the symbol.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.680\u2013685</ref> The Middle Kingdom, China, had a central mountain, [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun]], known in [[Taoism|Taoist literature]] as \"the mountain at the middle of the world.\" To \"go into the mountains\" meant to dedicate oneself to a spiritual life.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.681</ref> Monasteries of all faiths tend, like shrines, to be placed at elevated spots. Wise religious teachers are typically depicted in literature and art as bringing their revelations at world centers: mountains, trees, temples.\n\nBecause the axis mundi is an idea that unites a number of concrete images, no contradiction exists in regarding multiple spots as \"the center of the world\". The symbol can operate in a number of locales at once.<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1991. p.39\"/> [[Mount Hermon]] was regarded as the axis mundi in [[Canaanite]] tradition, from where the sons of God are introduced descending in [[1 Enoch]] (1En6:6).<ref name=\"Bautch2003\">{{cite book|author=Kelley Coblentz Bautch|title=A Study of the Geography of 1 Enoch 17\u201319: \"no One Has Seen what I Have Seen\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3FPNFEtWNrQC&pg=PA62|date=25 September 2003|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-13103-3|page=62}}</ref> The [[Urartu|ancient Armenians]] had a number of holy sites, the most important of which was [[Mount Ararat]], which was thought to be the home of the gods as well as the center of the Universe.<ref>http://www.peopleofar.com/2013/08/11/noahs-ark-in-the-mountains-of-armenia/</ref> Likewise, the [[Ancient Greece|ancient Greeks]] regarded several sites as places of earth's ''[[omphalos]]'' (navel) stone, notably the oracle at [[Delphi]], while still maintaining a belief in a cosmic [[world tree]] and in [[Mount Olympus]] as the abode of the gods. Judaism has the [[Temple Mount]], Christianity has the [[Mount of Olives]] and [[Calvary]], Islam has the [[Ka'aba]], said to be the first building on earth, and the [[Temple Mount]] ([[Dome of the Rock]]).  In [[Hinduism]], [[Mount Kailash]] is identified with the mythical [[Mount Meru]] and regarded as the home of [[Shiva]]; in [[Vajrayana Buddhism]], Mount Kailash is recognized as the most sacred place where all the [[Ley line|dragon currents]] converge and is regarded as the gateway to [[Shambhala]].  In [[Shinto]], the [[Ise Shrine]] is the omphalos.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}  In addition to the [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun Mountains]], where it is believed the [[peach tree of immortality]] is located, the [[Chinese folk religion]] recognizes four other specific mountains as pillars of the world.\n\nSacred places constitute world centers ([[omphalos]]) with the [[altar]] or place of prayer as the axis. Altars, incense sticks, candles and torches form the axis by sending a column of smoke, and prayer, toward heaven. The architecture of sacred places often reflects this role. \"Every temple or palace\u2014and by extension, every sacred city or royal residence\u2014is a Sacred Mountain, thus becoming a Centre.\"<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1971. p.12\">Mircea Eliade (tr. Willard Trask). 'Archetypes and Repetition' in ''The Myth of the Eternal Return. Princeton, 1971. {{ISBN|0691017778}}. p.12</ref> The [[stupa]] of [[Hinduism]], and later [[Buddhism]], reflects [[Mount Meru]]. Cathedrals are laid out in the form of a [[cross]], with the vertical bar representing the union of earth and heaven as the horizontal bars represent union of people to one another, with the altar at the intersection. [[Pagoda]] structures in Asian temples take the form of a stairway linking earth and heaven. A [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] in a church or a [[minaret]] in a mosque also serve as connections of earth and heaven. Structures such as the [[maypole]], derived from the [[Saxons]]' [[Irminsul]], and the [[totem pole]] among [[indigenous peoples of the Americas]] also represent world axes. The [[calumet (pipe)|calumet]], or sacred pipe, represents a column of smoke (the soul) rising form a world center.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.148\u2013149</ref> A [[mandala]] creates a world center within the boundaries of its two-dimensional space analogous to that created in three-dimensional space by a shrine.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.52-54</ref>\n\nIn the [[Classical element]]s and the Vedic [[Pancha Bhoota]] the axis mundi corresponds to [[Aether (mythology)|Aether]], the quintessence.\n\n[[File:yggdrasil.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Yggdrasil]], the World Ash in Norse myths]]\n\n===Plants===\nPlants often serve as images of the axis mundi. The image of the [[Cosmic Tree]] provides an axis symbol that unites three planes: sky (branches), earth (trunk) and underworld (roots).<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.42-45</ref> In some [[Pacific island]] cultures the [[banyan]] tree, of which the [[Bodhi tree]] is of the [[Sacred Fig]] variety, is the abode of ancestor spirits. In Hindu religion, the banyan tree is considered sacred and is called ''ashwath vriksha'' (\"I am banyan tree among trees\" \u2013 ''[[Bhagavad Gita]]''). It represents eternal life because of its seemingly ever-expanding branches.  The Bodhi tree is also the name given to the tree under which [[Gautama Siddhartha]], the historical [[Buddhahood|Buddha]], sat on the night he attained [[Bodhi|enlightenment]]. The [[Mesoamerican world tree]] connects the planes of the Underworld and the sky with that of the terrestrial realm.<ref>{{cite book |author=Miller, Mary |authorlink=Mary Miller (art historian) |author2=Karl Taube |year=1993 |title=The Gods and Symbols of Ancient Mexico and the Maya |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |page=[https://archive.org/details/godssymbolsofa00mill/page/186 186] |isbn=0500050686 |url=https://archive.org/details/godssymbolsofa00mill/page/186 |author2-link=Karl Taube }}</ref> The [[Yggdrasil]], or World Ash, functions in much the same way in [[Norse mythology]]; it is the site where [[Odin]] found enlightenment. Other examples include [[Jievaras]] in [[Lithuanian mythology]] and [[Thor's Oak]] in the myths of the pre-Christian [[Germanic peoples]]. The [[Tree of Life]] and the [[Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil]] in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] present two aspects of the same image. Each is said to stand at the center of the [[Garden of Eden|Paradise garden]] from which four rivers flow to nourish the whole world. Each tree confers a boon. [[Bamboo]], the plant from which Asian calligraphy pens are made, represents knowledge and is regularly found on Asian college campuses. The [[Christmas tree]], which can be traced in its origins back to pre-Christian [[Europe]]an beliefs, represents an axis mundi.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Chevalier, Jean and Gheerbrandt, Alain. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.1025\u20131033</ref> {{clarify span|[[Entheogen]]s (psychoactive substances) are often regarded as world axes|date=November 2012}}, such as the [[Fly Agaric]] mushroom among the [[Evenks]] of [[Russia]].{{citation needed|date=November 2012}} In China, traditional cosmography sometimes depicts the world center marked with the Jian tree ({{lang|zh|\u5efa\u6728}}). Two more trees are placed at the East and West, corresponding to the points of sunrise and sunset, as described in the ''[[Huainanzi]]''.\n\n[[File:Da Vinci Vitruve Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[Vitruvian Man]]'' by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] (c. 1492)]]\n\n===Human figure===\nThe human body can express the symbol of world axis.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Symbolism of the Centre' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.54</ref> Some of the more abstract Tree of Life representations, such as the ''[[sefirot]]'' in [[Kabbalism]] and in the ''[[chakra]]'' system recognized by Hinduism and Buddhism, merge with the concept of the human body as a pillar between heaven and earth. Disciplines such as [[yoga]] and [[tai chi]] begin from the premise of the human body as axis mundi. The Buddha represents a world centre in human form.<ref>Mircea Eliade (tr. Philip Mairet). 'Indian Symbolisms of Time and Eternity' in ''Images and Symbols. Princeton, 1991. {{ISBN|069102068X}}. p.76</ref> Large statues of a meditating figure unite the human figure with the symbolism of temple and tower. [[Astrology]] in all its forms assumes a connection between human health and affairs and the orientation of these with celestial bodies. World religions regard the body itself as a temple and prayer as a column uniting earth to heaven. The ancient [[Colossus of Rhodes]] combined the role of human figure with those of portal and skyscraper. The image of a human being suspended on a tree or a cross locates the figure at the axis where heaven and earth meet. The Renaissance image known as the [[Vitruvian Man]] represented a symbolic and mathematical exploration of the human form as world axis.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Homes===\nHomes can represent world centers. The symbolism for their residents is the same as for inhabitants of palaces and other sacred mountains.<ref name=\"Mircea Eliade 1971. p.12\"/> The hearth participates in the symbolism of the [[altar]] and a central [[garden]] participates in the symbolism of primordial [[Garden of Eden|paradise]]. In Asian cultures houses were traditionally laid out in the form of a square oriented toward the four compass directions. A traditional Asian home was oriented toward the sky through [[feng shui]], a system of [[geomancy]], just as a palace would be. Traditional Arab houses are also laid out as a square surrounding a central fountain that evokes a primordial garden paradise. Mircea Eliade noted that \"the symbolism of the pillar in [European] peasant houses likewise derives from the 'symbolic field' of the ''axis mundi''. In many archaic dwellings the central pillar does in fact serve as a means of communication with the heavens, with the sky.\"<ref>Mircea Eliade. 'Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i and Mythology' in ''Symbolism, the Sacred, and the Arts. Continuum, 1992. {{ISBN|0826406181}}. p. 100</ref> The nomadic peoples of Mongolia and the Americas more often lived in circular structures. The central pole of the tent still operated as an axis but a fixed reference to the four compass points was avoided.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.529\u2013531</ref>\n\n[[File:Caduceus large.jpg|thumb|110px|right|The [[caduceus]]]]\n\n===Shamanic function===\nA common [[shamanism|shamanic]] concept, and a universally told story, is that of the healer traversing the axis mundi to bring back knowledge from the other world. It may be seen in the stories from [[Odin]] and the [[Yggdrasil|World Ash Tree]] to [[the Garden of Eden]] and [[Jacob's Ladder]] to [[Jack and the Beanstalk]] and [[Rapunzel]]. It is the essence of the journey described in ''[[The Divine Comedy]]'' by [[Dante Alighieri]]. The epic poem relates its hero's descent and ascent through a series of spiral structures that take him from through the core of the earth, from the depths of Hell to celestial Paradise.\nIt is also a central tenet in the [[Southeastern Ceremonial Complex]].<ref>{{cite book |  last = Townsend | first = Richard F. |  title = Hero, Hawk, and Open Hand| publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | year = 2004 |  isbn = 0-300-10601-7| title-link = Hero, Hawk, and Open Hand }}</ref>\n\nAnyone or anything suspended on the axis between heaven and earth becomes a repository of potential knowledge. A special status accrues to the thing suspended: a [[Serpent (symbolism)|serpent]], a victim of crucifixion or hanging, a rod, a fruit, [[mistletoe]]. Derivations of this idea find form in the [[Rod of Asclepius]], an emblem of the medical profession, and in the [[caduceus]], an emblem of correspondence and commercial professions. The staff in these emblems represents the axis mundi while the [[Serpent (symbolism)|serpents]] act as guardians of, or guides to, knowledge.<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp.142\u2013145</ref>\n\n==Traditional expressions==\n\n===Asia===\n*[[Wuji (philosophy)|Wuji]]\n*[[Bodhi tree]], especially where [[Gautama Buddha]] found Enlightenment\n*[[Eight Pillars]]: eight axes mundi in Chinese mythology\n*[[Pagoda]]\n*[[Stupa]] in Buddhism\n*[[Mount Meru (mythology)|Mount Meru]] in Hinduism and Buddhism\n*[[Mount Kailash]] regarded by Hinduism and several religions in [[Tibet]], e.g. [[B\u00f6n]]\n*[[Jambudvipa]] in [[Hinduism]] and [[Jainism]] which is regarded as the actual navel of the [[Jain cosmology|universe]] (which is human in form)\n*[[Kailasa]] (India), the abode of [[Shiva]]\n*[[Mount Mandara|Mandara]] (India)\n*[[Shiva Lingam]] (India)\n*[[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun Mountain]] (China), residence of the Immortals and the site of [[Peaches of Immortality|a peach tree offering immortality]]\n*Human figure ([[yoga]], [[taiji|tai chi]], [[Buddha]] in [[meditation]], [[religious image|sacred images]] or [[icon]])\n* [[Ise Shrine]] ([[Shinto]])\n* Central courtyard in traditional home\n*[[Bamboo|Bamboo stalk]], associated with knowledge and learning\n*Mago Stronghold (Old Korea) also known as Mago-seong, Mago San-seong, Go-Seong, Halmi-seong. Primordial Home of the Great Goddess and her primordial descendants<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Mago Way: Re-discovering Mago, the Great Goddess from East Asia|last=Hwang|first=Helen Hye-Sook|publisher=Mago Books|year=2015|isbn=9781516907922|pages=136\u2013142}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East===\n*[[Garden of Eden]] with four rivers\n*[[Tree of Life]] and [[Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil]]\n*[[Mountains of Ararat|Mt. Ararat]] landing place of Noah's ark \n*[[Ziggurat]], or [[Tower of Babel]]\n*[[Jacob's Ladder]]\n*[[Jerusalem]], specifically, the [[Temple in Jerusalem|Holy Temple]]; focus of Jewish prayer where Abraham bound Isaac\n*[[Christian Cross|Cross of the Crucifixion]]\n*[[Steeple (architecture)|Steeple]]\n*[[Ka'aba]] in [[Mecca]]; focus of Muslim prayer\n*[[Qutb]], In Sufism, an intermediary figure between God and mankind\n*[[Dome of the Rock]] where [[Muhammad]], in Islam, is believed to have ascended to heaven\n*[[Minaret]]\n*[[Dilmun]]\n*[[Garizim]] (Samaria)\n*[[Hara Berezaiti]] (Persia)\n*[[Zaphon]]\n*[[Mount Qaf]]\n*[[Mount Carmel]]<ref>{{citation|last=Akerdahl|first=Per-Olof|date=2000|url=https://bahai-library.com/akerdahl_pilgrimage_religious_identity|chapter=Pilgrimage and Religious Identity in the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith|title=Lights of Irfan|publisher=Irfan Colloquia|location=Wilmette, IL|volume=1|pages=1-20}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n*[[Meskel]] bonfire\n*[[Stelae]] of the [[Aksumite Empire]]\n*[[Pyramids]] of [[Egypt]]\n*[[Osun-Osogbo]] Sacred Grove of [[Nigeria]]\n*[[Jebel Barkal]] of [[Sudan]]\n*[[Idafe Rock]] of [[Guanches|prehispanic]] [[La Palma]]\n*[[Mt Kenya]] of [[Kenya]]\n*[[Mount Kilimanjaro]]\n\n===Europe===\n*[[Yggdrasil]] (the world ash-tree in [[Norse cosmology]])\n*[[Irminsul]] (the great pillar in [[Germanic paganism]])\n*[[Hill of Uisneach]] (the navel and center of Ireland in [[Irish mythology]])<ref>Alwyn and Brinley Rees. ''Celtic Heritage''. Thames and Hudson: New York, 1961. {{ISBN|0500270392}}. pp. 159\u2013161.</ref>\n*[[Mount Olympus]] in Greece, court of the gods ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Sampo]] or Sammas ([[Finnic mythology|Baltic-Finnic mythology]])\n*[[Delphi]], home of the Oracle of Delphi ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Colossus of Rhodes]] ([[Greek mythology]])\n*[[Maypole]] ([[East Europe]] and [[Germanic paganism]])\n*[[Purgatorio]], [[Dante]]'s vision of Purgatory as a mountain ([[Christian poetry]])\n*[[Jack and the Beanstalk|Jack's Beanstalk]] ([[England|English]] [[fairy tale]])\n*[[Rapunzel|Rapunzel's Tower]] ([[Germany|German]] fairy tale)\n*[[Hearth]]\n*Central pillar of peasant homes\n*[[Altar]]\n*[[Vitruvian Man]]\n*[[Hagia Sophia]]\n*[[St. Peter's Basilica]]\n*[[Umbilicus urbis Romae]], a structure in the [[Roman Forum]] from where all the [[Roman road]]s parted.\n*[[Isle of Man]] ([[Emain Ablach]], the gate to the Otherworld in Irish Mythology)\n\n===The Americas===\n* Julia's Hamok under Haiwana\n*[[Teotihuac\u00e1n|Teotihuac\u00e1n Pyramids]]\n*[[Totem Pole]]\n*[[Rehue]]\n*[[Potomitan]]\n*[[Tent]]\n*[[Black Hills]] ([[Sioux]])\n*[[Calumet (pipe)|Calumet]] (sacred pipe)\n*[[Sipapu]] ([[Hopi]])\n*[[Southeastern Ceremonial Complex]]\n*[[Medicine wheel]]s of the northern [[Great Plains]]\n*[[Temple Lot]] ([[Mormonism]])\n*[[Cuzco]] ([[Incas]]), meaning \"navel\" in [[Quechua languages|Quechua]]{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n*[[Chakana]]\n*[[Mesoamerican world tree]]\n*[[Lanzon]]\n*[[Turtle Island (North America)|Turtle Island]]\n*[[Yvy marae]], the sacred land \"free from all evil\", whose pursuit led to the colonization of lowland South America by the [[Tup\u00ed people|Tup\u00ed]] and [[Guaran\u00ed people|Guaran\u00ed]] peoples, guided by the [[karai (Tup\u00ed-Guaran\u00ed culture)|karai]] or priests<ref>CASCUDO, L. C. ''Geografia dos mitos brasileiros. ''3\u00aa edi\u00e7\u00e3o. S\u00e3o Paulo. Global. 2002. p. 133.</ref><ref>CLASTRES, P. ''Le grand parler''. Paris: \u00c9ditions du seuil, '975. p. 9</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tekoamboytyitarypu.site90.com/index.php?news&nid=9 |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000659/http://www.tekoamboytyitarypu.site90.com/index.php?news&nid=9 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Sul\u00e1yom]] in [[Talamancan mythology]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Diccionario de mitolog\u00eda bribri|last=Jara, Carla Victoria, 1961\u2013|date=2003|publisher=Editorial de la Universidad de Costa Rica|others=Garc\u00eda Segura, Al\u00ed.|isbn=9977677387|edition=1|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|pages=196\u2013197|language=Spanish|oclc=53238389}}</ref>\n\n===Australia===\n*[[Uluru]]\n*[[Rainbow Serpent|Rainbow Snake]]\n\n==Modern expressions==\n{{see also|North\u2013South divide|East\u2013West dichotomy}}\n[[File:101.tall.altonthompson.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Taipei 101]] ([[Taiwan]])]]\n{{Synthesis|date=November 2008}}\nAxis mundi symbolism continues to be evoked, even in modern societies, through various art forms and has a deep rooted spiritual inspiration that transcends time.\n\nThe idea has proven consequential in the realm of [[architecture]].  Structures that have a spiritual meaning, that inspire and create a connection between the spiritual world and the physical world, that are erected as monuments to commemorate are achievements can be considered to be inspired by the axis mundi. The pyramids that have been erected throughout human history serve as perfect examples of axis mundi.  A [[skyscraper]], as the term itself suggests, suggests the connection of earth and sky, as do [[spire]] structures of all sorts. Such buildings come to be regarded as \"centers\" of an inhabited area, or even the world, and serve as icons of its ideals.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. p.137</ref> The first skyscraper of modern times, the [[Eiffel Tower]], exemplifies this role. The structure was erected in 1889 in [[Paris]], [[France]], to serve as the centerpiece for the [[Exposition Universelle (1889)|Exposition Universelle]], making it a symbolic world center from the planning stages. It has served as an iconic image for the city and the nation ever since.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. p. 19</ref> Landmark skyscrapers often take names that clearly identify them as centers.<ref>Judith Dupr\u00e9. 'Skyscrapers: A History of the World's Most Extraordinary Buildings.' Black Dog & Leventhal, 1998/2008. pp. 45, 69, 81, 91, 97,135, 136, 143</ref>\n\nArtistic representations of the axis mundi are plentiful. Just one example of these is the ''Colonne sans fin'' (''[[The Endless Column]]'', 1938) an abstract [[sculpture]] by Romanian [[Constantin Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i]]. The column takes the form of a \"sky pillar\" ({{lang|ro|{{vanchor|columna cerului}}}}) upholding the heavens even as its rhythmically repeating segments invite climb and suggest the possibility of ascension.<ref>Mircea Eliade. 'Br\u00e2ncu\u0219i and Mythology' in ''Symbolism, the Sacred, and the Arts. Continuum, 1992. {{ISBN|0826406181}}. p.99-100</ref>\n\nVisual representation of the axis mundi in contemporary art is currently being achieved by photographer Jennifer Westjohn.  By the process of mirror symmetry of a single photograph the artist exposes an entirely new image: the 5th point.  The viewer is then introduced to a coalescing of nature and the universe which lends new perspective to the original image.  This artistic representation of axis mundi opens the mind up to a new visual dimension both energistic and shamanic.<ref>Jennifer Westjohn. Photographer. \"jenniferwestjohn.com\" \"the5thpoint.com\" 2013\u20132017</ref>\n\nAxis mundi symbolism exists in modern [[Spaceflight|space travel]].<ref>Jean Chevalier and Alain Gheerbrandt. ''A Dictionary of Symbols''. Penguin Books: London, 1996. {{ISBN|0140512543}}. pp. 18, 1020\u20131022</ref> Each astronaut embarks on a perilous journey into the heavens, per se, and if successful, returns with a boon for dissemination. The [[Apollo 13]] insignia stated it succinctly: ''Ex luna scientia'' (\"From the Moon, knowledge\").<ref>[http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/history/apollo/apollo-13/apollo-13.html Nasa Apollo Mission: Apollo 13. 2007-08-25]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Alchemy]]\n*[[Celestial sphere]]\n*[[Comparative mythology]]\n*[[Crucifix]]\n*[[Fertile Crescent]]\n*[[Fleur de lis]]\n*[[Herma]]\n*[[History of the center of the Universe]]\n*[[Hyperborea]]\n*[[North pole]]\n*[[Optical axis]]\n*[[Palmette]]\n*[[Phurba]]\n*[[Taiji (philosophy)]]\n*[[Vorticism]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|group=lungring}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Axis Mundi}}\n[[Category:Comparative mythology]]\n[[Category:Esoteric cosmology]]\n[[Category:Geographical centres]]\n[[Category:History of astrology]]\n[[Category:History of religion]]\n[[Category:Mythological cosmologies]]\n[[Category:Mythological places]]\n[[Category:Panentheism]]\n[[Category:Pantheism]]\n[[Category:Religious symbols]]\n[[Category:Shamanism]]\n[[Category:Spirituality]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCanaanite(link changed toCanaan) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axis_mundi"}
{"title_page": "Peter Navarro", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Economist and member of the Trump administration}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter Navarro\n| image = Peter Navarro official photo.jpg\n| office = Director of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = April 29, 2017\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor =\n| office1 = Director of the [[National Trade Council]]\n| president1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start1 = January 20, 2017\n| term_end1 = April 29, 2017\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1 = Office dissolved\n|birth_name=Peter Kent Navarro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|7|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Peter Kent Navarro''' (born July 15, 1949) is an American economist and author. He serves in the Trump administration as the Assistant to the President, Director of Trade and Manufacturing Policy, and the national [[Defense Production Act]] policy coordinator. He previously served as a Deputy Assistant to the President and Director of the [[White House National Trade Council]], a newly created entity in the [[Executive Branch of the United States|executive branch]] of the U.S. government, until it was folded into the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], a new role established by executive order in April 2017.<ref name=\"joshwapo\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He is also a professor emeritus of [[economics]] and [[public policy]] at the [[Paul Merage School of Business]], [[University of California, Irvine]], and the author of ''[[Death by China]], among other publications.''<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nNavarro's views on trade are significantly outside the mainstream of economic thought, and are widely considered fringe and misguided by other economists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/02/trump-s-cabinet The wonkless White House], ''Economist'' (February 2017): \"Mr Navarro's views on trade are well outside the mainstream, and he is not a big hitter in academic circles.\"</ref><ref name=\"Coy\">Peter Coy, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-08/after-defeating-cohn-trump-s-trade-warrior-is-on-the-rise-again After Defeating Cohn, Trump's Trade Warrior Is on the Rise Again], Bloomberg (March 8, 2018): \"Navarro has come a long way from his roots as a mainstream economist.\"</ref> A strong proponent of reducing [[U.S. trade deficit]]s, Navarro is well known as a critic of Germany and China and has accused both nations of currency manipulation.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lowrey |first1=Annie |title=The 'Madman' Behind Trump's Trade Theory |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/peter-navarro-trump-trade/573913/ |date=December 2018 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He has called for increasing the size of the [[manufacturing in the United States|American manufacturing sector]], setting high tariffs, and \"repatriating global supply chains\". He is also a strong opponent of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nNavarro was born on July 15, 1949, in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/candidates/election.guide/text/CA49.shtml|title=AllPolitics \u2013 Congressional Races \u2013 California District 49|website=www.cnn.com}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{cite magazine |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |title=Peter Navarro Used To Be a Democrat. Now He's the Mastermind Behind Trump's Trade War |url=http://time.com/5375727/peter-navarro/ |date=August 23, 2018 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Navarro's father, Alfred \"Al\" Navarro, a saxophonist and clarinetist, led a [[house band]], which played summers in [[New Hampshire]] and winters in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99097793/|title=Orchestra Leader is Dead from Detroit, Michigan on January 2, 1972 \u00b7 Page 32|newspaper= Detroit Free Press |accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was 9 or 10.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-05-02/trump-s-trade-warrior-is-the-most-unpopular-economist-in-the-class|title=Trump's Trade Warrior Is the Most Unpopular Economist in the Class|date=May 2, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>  Subsequently, he lived with his mother, Evelyn Littlejohn, a [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] secretary, in [[Palm Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-08/local/me-4514_1_peter-navarro|title=Navarro Says Loan for Race Was Inherited: Mayoral candidate admits $300,000 was given to him by his mother, but all the money has been spent|first=Leonard|last=Bernstein|date=August 8, 1992|newspaper=LA Times|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> He lived in [[Bethesda, Maryland]] in a one-bedroom apartment with his mother and brother during his teenage years.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nNavarro went to [[Tufts University]] on a full academic scholarship,<ref name=\":23\" /> graduating in 1972 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He then spent three years in the [[Peace Corps|U.S. Peace Corps]], serving in Thailand.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\"cv\" /> He earned a [[Master of Public Administration]] from [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in 1979, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Economics]] from Harvard under the supervision of [[Richard E. Caves]] in 1986.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web |url=https://merage.uci.edu/_files/documents/faculty-profiles/Navarro-Peter-CV.pdf|title= Peter Navarro Curriculum Vitae |last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=August 2016|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Policy analysis===\nNavarro's policy prescriptions include that \"U.S. should be tough on trade, crack down on intellectual property theft, tax Chinese exports, combat Chinese mercantilism, [and] bring jobs home.\"<ref name=ct />\n\n===Academic career===\nFrom 1981 through 1985, he was a research associate at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]'s Energy and Environmental Policy Center. From 1985 through 1988, he taught at the [[University of California, San Diego]] and the [[University of San Diego]].<ref name = UT>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-peter-navarro-tariffs-san-diego-20180306-htmlstory.html |title=Former San Diego politician Peter Navarro is fighting for Trump's tariffs|last=Hamblin|first=Abby|date=March 6, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> In 1989 he moved to the [[University of California, Irvine]] as a professor of economics and public policy. He continued on the UC Irvine faculty for more than 20 years and is now a professor emeritus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://merage.uci.edu/research-faculty/faculty-directory/Peter-Navarro.html|title=Faculty Directory|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He has worked on energy issues and the relationship between the United States and [[Asia]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|title=Peter Navarro Bio |last=Navarro |first=Peter|website=The Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103004035/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|archivedate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> He has received multiple teaching awards for [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] courses he has taught.<ref name=PMSB-Awards />\n\nAs a doctoral student in 1984, Navarro wrote a book entitled ''The Policy Game: How Special Interests and Ideologues are Stealing America'', which discussed that special interest groups had led the United States to \"a point in its history where it cannot grow and prosper.\" In the book he also called for greater worker's compensation to help those who had lost jobs to trade and foreign competition. His doctoral thesis on why corporations donate to charity is one of his most highly-cited works. He has also done research in the topic of wind energy with Frank Harris, a former student of his.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Publications===\nNavarro is a prolific author with over a dozen books written on various topics in economics and specializing in issues of balance of trade. He has published peer-reviewed economics research on energy policy, charity, deregulation and the economics of trash collection.<ref name=\"ct\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-08-01/peter-navarro-is-the-economist-whose-ideas-guide-trump|title=Here's the Economist Whose Ideas Guide Trump|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|author-link=Tyler Cowen|date=August 1, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Google Scholar Citations |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=usrEMP4AAAAJ&hl=en |website=scholar.google.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Navarro \"is a prolific writer, but has no publications in top-tier academic journals... [although] his research interests are broader than the average economist\u2019s.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/briefing/2017/01/21/peter-navarro-is-about-to-become-one-of-the-worlds-most-powerful-economists|title=Peter Navarro is about to become one of the world's most powerful economists|journal=The Economist|access-date=December 8, 2018|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' is a book published by [[Financial Times|FT Press]] in (2006). Navarro examines China as an emerging [[world power]] confronting challenges at home and abroad as it struggles to exert itself in the [[economic globalization|global market]]. He also discusses how China's role in international commerce is creating conflicts with nations around the world over energy, natural resources, the environment, [[intellectual property]], and other issues. A review in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' describes the book as \"comprehensive\" and \"contemporary\" and concludes that it \"will teach readers to understand the dragon, just not how to vanquish it\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6386391.html?q=The+Coming+China+Wars ''Publishers Weekly review of The Coming China Wars], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', October 30, 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Professor Peter Navarro of the Business School at University of California, Irvine talks his work \"Death by China\" and how China cheats in the world trade system @ University of Michigan-4.jpg|thumb|Professor Peter Navarro discusses his work, ''[[Death by China]]'', arguing China cheats in the world trade system at [[University of Michigan]] in 2012]]\n''[[Death by China]]'' (2011) is a book by Navarro and Greg Autry. According to ''The Economist'', \"the core allegations Mr. Navarro makes against China are not all that controversial. He accuses China of keeping its currency cheap . . . He deplores China\u2019s practice of forcing American firms to hand over intellectual property as a condition of access to its market. He notes, correctly, that Chinese firms pollute the environment more freely and employ workers in far worse conditions than American rules allow.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro argues that China violates fair trade by \"illegal export subsidies and currency manipulation, effectively flooding the U.S. markets\" and unfairly making it \"virtually impossible\" for American companies to compete.<ref name=rs>{{cite web|title=Review: 'Death by China' |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948072?refcatid=31|website=Variety|author=Ronnie Scheib|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> It is a critique of \"global capitalism\" including foreign labor practices and environmental protection.<ref name=\"Salon\">Andrew O'Hehir, [http://www.salon.com/2012/08/22/chinas_not_so_secret_plan_for_world_domination/ \"China\u2019s not-so-secret plan for world domination\"], ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'', August 21, 2012.</ref> Currency manipulation and subsidies are stated as reasons that \"American companies cannot compete because they're not competing with Chinese companies, they're competing with the Chinese government.\"<ref name=ng>[[Neil Genzlinger]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/24/movies/death-by-china-documentary-directed-by-peter-navarro.html \"Casting Blame for Jobs That Vanish\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 23, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Navarro directed and produced a [[documentary film]] based on his book, ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins |first1=Olivera |title=Economist Peter Navarro says U.S. manufacturing is suffering 'Death by China' |url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2012/09/film_says_us_manufacturing_is.html|website=The Cleveland Plain Dealer |accessdate=January 19, 2017|date=September 7, 2012}}</ref> The film, described as \"fervently anti-China\",<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Katie|last=Quan|year=2017|title=Prospects for US-China Union Relations in the Era of Xi and Trump|journal=International Union Rights|page=13|volume=24|issue=4|doi=10.14213/inteuniorigh.24.4.0011 }}</ref> was released under the same title and narrated by [[Martin Sheen]]. From 2011 until 2016, Navarro was a frequent guest on the radio program the John Batchelor Show.\n\n===Political career===\n\n====Politics and campaigns for public office====\nWhile teaching at UC Irvine, Navarro ran unsuccessfully for office in [[San Diego, California]] five times.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name = UT/> In 1992, he [[San Diego mayoral election, 1992|ran for mayor]], finishing first (38.2%) in the primary, but lost with 48% to [[Susan Golding]] in the runoff.<ref name=CSD-M /> During his mayoral campaign, Navarro ran on a no-growth platform.<ref name=\"SanDiegoSprawl\">{{Cite book|title=The Failure of Planning: Permitting Sprawl in San Diego Suburbs, 1970\u20131999|last=Hogan|first=Richard|publisher=[[Ohio State University Press]]|year=2002|isbn=978-0814251041|location=United States|page=[https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119 119]|url=https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119}}</ref> In 1993, he ran for San Diego city council and in 1994 for San Diego County board of supervisors.<ref name = UT/> In 1996, he ran for the [[California's 49th congressional district|49th Congressional District]] as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee, but lost to Republican [[Brian Bilbray]], 52.7% to 41.9%.<ref name=BP-CA49 /> In 2001, Navarro ran in a special election to fill the District 6 San Diego city council seat, but lost in a special election with 7.85% of the vote.<ref name=CSD-CD6 />\n\nNavarro supported President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[phase-out of incandescent light bulbs]], the adoption of [[Wind power|wind energy]], and [[carbon tax]]es in order to stop [[global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/a-pit-bull-for-climate-could-soon-sit-next-to-trump/|title=A \"Pit Bull\" for Climate Could Soon Sit Next to Trump|last=News|first=Robin Bravender,Zack Colman,E&E|work=Scientific American|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Trump campaign advisor ====\nIn 2016, Navarro served as an economic policy adviser to Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"appoint\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/greatagain/navarro-national-trade-council-c2d90c10eacb|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Appoints Dr. Peter Navarro to Head the White House National Trade Council|first=The Transition|last=Team|date=December 21, 2016|website=Medium}}</ref> He advocated for an [[Isolationism|isolationist]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] American foreign policy.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|title=White House At A Crossroads After Cohn|last=Soergel|first=Andrew|date=March 7, 2018|website=US News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308014013/https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Navarro and the international private equity investor [[Wilbur Ross]] authored an economic plan for Trump campaign in September 2016.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan|title=New White Paper on Donald J. Trump's Economic Plan |website=www.donaldjtrump.com|access-date=March 6, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045918/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan |archivedate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Navarro was invited to be an adviser after [[Jared Kushner]], while he was researching China for Trump, saw on Amazon that Navarro co-wrote ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref name=\"Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon\">{{cite web|last1=Vladimirov|first1=Nikita|title=Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/328969-report-kushner-found-trump-economic-advisor-navarro-by-browsing|website=TheHill|accessdate=April 18, 2017|language=English|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> When told that the [[Tax Policy Center]] assessment of Trump's economic plan would reduce federal revenues by $6 trillion and reduce economic growth in the long term, Navarro said that the analysis demonstrated \"a high degree of analytical and political malfeasance\".<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/10/24/trumps-advisers-see-another-conspiracy-far-from-the-campaign-trail/|title=Trump's advisers see another conspiracy \u2013 far from the campaign trail|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> When the Peterson Institute for International Affairs estimated that Trump's economic plan would cost millions of Americans their jobs, Navarro said that writers at the Peterson Institute \"weave a false narrative and they come up with some phony numbers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2016/09/19/trump-adviser-bullish-wake-tax-trade-critiques/ |title=Trump Adviser Bullish in Wake of Tax, Trade Critiques|last=Rainey|first=Ryan|date=September 19, 2016|website=Morning Consult |access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> According to MIT economist [[Simon Johnson (economist)|Simon Johnson]], the economic plan essay authored by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Donald Trump during the campaign had projections \"based on assumptions so unrealistic that they seem to have come from a different planet. If the United States really did adopt Trump's plan, the result would be an immediate and unmitigated disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/trump-insane-economic-plan-by-simon-johnson-2016-09?barrier=accessreg|title=Trump's Magical Economic Thinking|last=Johnson|first=Simon|date=September 30, 2016 |work=Project Syndicate|access-date=March 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When 370 economists, including nineteen Nobel laureates, signed a letter warning against Donald Trump's stated economic policies in November 2016, Navarro said that the letter was \"an embarrassment to the corporate offshoring wing of the economist profession who continues to insist bad trade deals are good for America.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-of-prominent-us-economists-warn-against-voting-trump/|title=Hundreds of US economists warn against voting Trump|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, with [[Wilbur Ross]] and [[Andy Puzder]], Navarro co-authored the essay titled \"Economic Analysis of Donald Trump's Contract with the American Voter\".<ref>[[Wilbur Ross]], [[Andy Puzder]] & Peter Navarro, [http://www.publicnow.com/view/26F924AB8FA783A28FEA3EE8943635B4F0574556?2016-10-31-14:32:09+00:00-xxx4035]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald J. Trump for President, Inc.]], October 30, 2016</ref>\n\n====White House trade advisor====\n[[File:Peter Navarro, Director of the White House National Trade Council, Addresses in the Oval Office before U.S. President Donald Trump Signs Executive Orders Regarding Trade on March 31, 2017 4.jpg|thumb|Director Peter Navarro addresses President [[Donald Trump]]'s promises to American people, workers, and domestic manufacturers ('''[https://assets.donaldjtrump.com/DJT_DeclaringAmericanEconomicIndependence.pdf Declaring American Economic Independence]''' on June 28, 2016) in the [[Oval Office]] with [[U.S. Vice President|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] and [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Wilbur Ross]] before President Trump signs [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Orders]] regarding trade in March 2017<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-regarding-omnibus-report-significant-trade Presidential Executive Order Regarding the Omnibus Report on Significant Trade Deficits], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-establishing-enhanced-collection-and Presidential Executive Order on Establishing Enhanced Collection and Enforcement of Antidumping and Countervailing Duties and Violations of Trade and Customs Laws], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref>]]\nOn December 21, 2016, Navarro was selected by President-elect Trump to head a newly created position, as director of the [[White House National Trade Council]].<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title='Death by China' author to lead Trump trade office|url=https://www.ft.com/content/71a201d2-c7b3-11e6-8f29-9445cac8966f|website=www.ft.com|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> He outlines President Trump's trade policy as aiming to create jobs, revive the manufacturing sector, and improve the country's trade balance. He warned that trade deficits could jeopardize U.S. national security by allowing unfriendly nations to encroach on American supply chains. One of his main missions is to focus on behaviors by other countries that he considers abusive, cheating, illegal, and unfair against the U.S.<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4659659/peter-navarro-outlines-trump-administration-trade-policy-priorities Peter Navarro Outlines Trump Administration Trade Policy Priorities], [[C-SPAN]], June 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/videos/2017-03-31/navarro-says-not-all-trade-deficits-necessarily-bad-video Peter Navarro Says Trade Deficits Aren't Always Bad], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], March 31, 2017</ref>\n\n====Director of Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy====\nIn April 2017, the National Trade Council became part of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], of which Navarro was appointed Director.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news| last1=Cook | first1=Nancy | last2=Restuccia | first2=Andrew |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/peter-navarro-trump-trade-240611|title=Trump's trade warrior prowls the West Wing|date=July 17, 2017|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> By September 2017, the Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy had been folded into the National Economic Council, which meant that Navarro would report to NEC Director [[Gary Cohn (investment banker)|Gary Cohn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/27/peter-navarro-trade-office-national-economic-council-243217|title=Kelly folds Navarro's trade shop into National Economic Council|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, several media outlets reported that Navarro's influence in the administration was rising again and that he would likely be promoted from the secondary billet of Deputy Assistant to the President to Assistant to the President, giving Navarro parity with the NEC Director.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Swanson | first1=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, a Top Trade Skeptic, Is Ascendant | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/25/us/politics/peter-navarro-trade.html | date=February 25, 2018 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Lynch | first1=David J. | last2=Damian | first2=Paletta | title=Trump Tilts Toward Hard-Liners Ahead of Key Trade Decisions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/trump-tilts-toward-hard-liners-ahead-of-key-trade-decisions/2018/02/26/ffe93e46-1b32-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html | date=February 26, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Josh Rogin]], writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', reported that Navarro had used his prior time of lower influence to lead several low-profile policy items, such as working to increase military funding, drafting [[:s:Executive Order 13806|Executive Order 13806]], and leading the effort to solve a dispute between the United States and [[Qatar]] over the Open Skies Agreement between the two countries.<ref name=\"joshwapo\">{{cite news | last1=Rogin | first1=Josh | title=How Peter Navarro Got His Groove Back | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2018/02/27/how-peter-navarro-got-his-groove-back/ | date=February 27, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn explaining his role in the Trump administration, Navarro said that he is there to \"provide the underlying analytics that confirm [Trump's] intuition [on trade]. And his intuition is always right in these matters.\"<ref name=\"Coy\" />\n\nIn June 2018, Navarro said that there was \"a special place in hell\" for Justin Trudeau, the Prime Minister of Canada, after Trudeau said that Canada would respond with retaliatory tariffs since the United States had placed tariffs on Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/10/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Peter Navarro says 'there's a special place in hell' for Justin Trudeau|last= Watkins|first=Eli|work=CNN|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> The Prime Minister's point-of-view and Canada's response to these tariffs were already public and well-known when Navarro made this comment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/white-house-adviser-kudlow-trump-trudeau-g7-summit-blame-1.4700061|title='Special place in hell': Trump advisers blast Trudeau for comments at G7 summit {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>  Navarro later apologized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/12/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Navarro sorry after saying there's a 'special place in hell' for Trudeau|first=Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Navarro said that Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States as \"a brilliant move\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/31/mnuchin-and-lighthizer-were-opposed-to-trump-tariffs-on-mexico-source-says.html|title=Mnuchin and Lighthizer opposed Trump tariffs on Mexico, source says|last=Higgins|first=Kayla Tausche,Tucker|date=2019-05-31|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, after being tasked by the President to combat China's usage of international mail rates to more cheaply ship products into the US, Navarro successfully led a diplomatic effort to the third Extraordinary Congress of the [[Universal Postal Union]] where it agreed member countries could be able to opt-in to self-declare their rates starting in July 2020, after repeated threats from the Trump administration to leave the UPU unless global postage rates were changed so countries like China could no longer unfairly benefit from international delivery prices, particularly when it came to e-commerce deliveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/26/trump-scores-a-big-victory-on-stamps-postal-union-terminal-dues-china/|title=Trump Scores a Big Victory-on Stamps|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-un-postal/u-n-postal-union-clinches-deal-to-keep-u-s-in-club-idUSKBN1WA247|title=U.N. postal union clinches deal to keep U.S. in club|last= Nebehay|first=Stephanie|work=Reuters|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavarro continued to promote policies challenging amid trade negotiations between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Schlesinger | first1=Jacob M. | last2=Salama | first2=Vivian | title=New White House Report, Authored by Trade Hawk, Blasts Chinese 'Economic Aggression'  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-white-house-report-authored-by-trade-hawk-blasts-chinese-economic-aggression-1529456401 | date=June 19, 2018 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=In the Battles Over Trump's Trade Wars, Hawkish Adviser Navarro Endures  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-the-battles-over-trumps-trade-wars-hawkish-adviser-navarro-endures-11576943074 | date=December 21, 2019 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Rappeport | first1=Alan | last2=Swanson | first2=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, Trump's Trade Warrior, Has Not Made His Peace With China | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/26/us/politics/peter-navarro-china-trade.html | date=December 26, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro worked with the DHS to initiate a crackdown on counterfeited and pirated e-commerce goods from overseas,<ref>{{cite web | last1=Shepardson | first1=David | title=U.S. to unveil crackdown on counterfeit, pirated e-commerce goods | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-counterfeiting/u-s-to-unveil-crackdown-on-counterfeit-pirated-e-commerce-goods-idUSKBN1ZN02E | date=January 23, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/us/politics/us-cracks-down-on-counterfeits-in-a-warning-shot-to-china.html |title=U.S. Cracks Down on Counterfeits in a Warning Shot to China - The New York Times |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= January 24, 2020|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mauldin | first1=William | last2=Leary | first2=Alex | title=U.S. Signals Crackdown on Counterfeit Goods Sold Online  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-signals-crackdown-on-counterfeit-goods-sold-online-11579820400 | date=January 24, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/24/dhs-report-targets-online-counterfeit-sales-on-amazon-e-commerce.html |title=DHS report targets online counterfeit sales on Amazon, e-commerce |publisher=Cnbc.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and he promoted the administration's actions on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jessica Bursztynsky |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/16/navarro-to-amazon-ebay-china-trade-deal-cracks-down-on-counterfeits.html |title=Navarro to Amazon, eBay: China trade deal cracks down on counterfeits |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=2020-01-16 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Peter |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/perspectives/peter-navarro-e-commerce-counterfeit-products/index.html |title=Navarro: Counterfeits harm Americans and threaten national security. Trump has a plan to combat them (opinion) |publisher=CNN |date=2020-01-31 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> Trump signed an executive order on the matter on January 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web | title=Trump signs executive order aimed at preventing sales of counterfeit goods from overseas | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-shipments/trump-signs-executive-order-aimed-at-preventing-sales-of-counterfeit-goods-from-overseas-idUSKBN1ZU35P | date=January 31, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, it was reported that Navarro was conducting his own investigation into the identity of the author of [[I Am Part of the Resistance Inside the Trump Administration|an anonymous op-ed in ''The New York Times'']] criticizing the Trump Administration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Suebsaeng | first1=Asawin | last2=Markay | first2=Lachlan | title=Trump's Top Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Has a Side Project: Secretly Hunting for 'Anonymous' | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-top-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-has-a-side-project-secretly-hunting-for-anonymous | date=February 17, 2020 | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Infrastructure plan====\nDuring the campaign Navarro, together with [[Wilbur Ross]] who became Trump's [[Commerce Secretary]], designed a $1 trillion infrastructure development plan for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name=\"peternavarro.com\">{{cite web|url=http://peternavarro.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/infrastructurereport.pdf|title=Infrastructure report|date=|publisher=peternavarro.com|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> The plan called for $137 billion in tax credits to private business to induce them to financing the bulk of infrastructure spending. Economists across the political spectrum derided the proposal.<ref name=\"Mufson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/economists-pan-infrastructure-plan-championed-by-trump-nominees/2017/01/17/0ed1ad5e-dc5e-11e6-918c-99ede3c8cafa_story.html|title=Economists pan infrastructure plan championed by Trump nominees|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=January 17, 2017|via=www.washingtonpost.com|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> Trump released a $1.5 trillion version of this plan in February 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/infrastructure/373408-white-house-releases-55-page-infrastructure-proposal|title=White House releases 55-page, $1.5 trillion infrastructure plan|first=Mallory|last=Shelbourne|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> but the Republican-controlled Congress showed little enthusiasm for the proposal, with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] reporting, \"President Trump's infrastructure plan appears to have crashed and burned in Congress\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/377681-trumps-infrastructure-push-hits-wall-in-congress|title=Trump's infrastructure push hits wall in Congress|first=Dustin|last=Weaver|date=March 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Navarro memo====\nOn January 29, 2020 Navarro issued a memo warning that coronavirus could \"evolv[e] into a full-blown pandemic, imperiling the lives of millions of Americans\" and that the \"risk of a worst-case pandemic scenario should not be overlooked\". He argued for restrictions on travel from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trade Adviser Warned White House in January of Risks of a Pandemic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/us/politics/navarro-warning-trump-coronavirus.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n====National Defense Production Act policy coordinator====\nOn March 27, 2020, Trump appointed Navarro to coordinate the federal government's [[Defense Production Act]] policy response during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489938-trump-names-new-defense-production-act-coordinator-for-coronavirus|title=Trump names new Defense Production Act coordinator for coronavirus fight|first=Morgan|last=Chalfant|date=March 27, 2020|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Pappas | first1=Alex | title=Trump appoints Navarro to lead Defense Production Act efforts after forcing GM to make ventilators | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-aide-navarro-lead-defense-production-act-efforts | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=\u2018This is War\u2019: President\u2019s Equipment Czar to Use Full Powers to Fight Coronavirus | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-is-war-presidents-equipment-czar-to-use-full-powers-to-fight-coronavirus-11585435836 | date=March 28, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views on trade ==\n{{main|International trade|Commercial policy|Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign}}\nNavarro has been a staunch critic of trade with China and strong proponent of reducing U.S. trade deficits. He has attacked Germany, Japan and China for currency manipulation. He has called for increasing the size of the American manufacturing sector, setting high tariffs, and repatriating global supply chains. He was a fierce opponent of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\nAccording to [[Bloomberg News]], Navarro had \"roots as a mainstream economist\" as he voiced support for free trade in his 1984 book ''The Policy Game''. He changed his positions as he saw \"the globalist erosion of the American economy\" develop.<ref name=\"Coy\"/>\n\nAccording to ''Politico'', Navarro's economic theories are \"considered fringe\" by his fellow economists.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2017/03/trump-trade-attack-dog-peter-navarro-000353|title=Trump's attack dog on trade|last=|first=|date=|work=The Agenda|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> A ''New Yorker'' reporter described Navarro's views on trade and China as so radical \"that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/trumps-muse-on-u-s-trade-with-china|title=Trump's Muse on U.S. Trade with China|last=|first=|date=October 12, 2016|website=The New Yorker|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's views on trade and China are so radical, however, that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.}}</ref> The ''Economist'' described Navarro as having \"oddball views\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21721937-donald-trumps-economic-strategy-unimaginative-and-incoherent-cooking-up-economic-policy|title=Cooking up an economic policy|website=The Economist|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> The George Mason University economist [[Tyler Cowen]] has described him as \"one of the most versatile and productive American economists of the last few decades\", but Cowen noted that he disagreed with his views on trade, which he claimed go \"against a strong professional consensus.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> University of Michigan economist [[Justin Wolfers]] described Navarro's views as \"far outside the mainstream,\" noting that \"he endorses few of the key tenets of\" the economics profession.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/upshot/why-most-economists-are-so-worried-about-trump.html|title=Why Most Economists Are So Worried About Trump|last=Wolfers|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|access-date=January 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331|quote=the only official who identifies as an economist\u2014Peter Navarro, who earned a Harvard Ph.D. in economics and will head up the newly formed National Trade Council\u2014stands so far outside the mainstream that he endorses few of the key tenets of the profession.|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> According to Lee Branstetter, economics professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University|Carnegie Mellon]] and trade expert with the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], Navarro \"was never a part of the group of economists who ever studied the global free-trade system ... He doesn't publish in journals. What he's writing and saying right now has nothing to do with what he got his Harvard Ph.D. in ... he doesn't do research that would meet the scientific standards of that community.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://businessinsider.com/what-is-trumpenomics-according-to-peter-navarro-2017-1|title=The clearest articulation of what Trump wants to do to America's economy comes from one person|last=|first=|date=|work=Business Insider|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Marcus Noland, an economist at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, described a tax and trade paper written by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Trump as \"a complete misunderstanding of international trade, on their part.\"<ref name=\":82\"/>\n\nIn August 2019, Navarro asserted the tariffs of the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]] were not hurting Americans. Citing extensive evidence to the contrary, Politifact rated Navarro's assertion \"Pants on Fire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/aug/20/peter-navarro/donald-trumps-tariffs-china-dont-hurt-americans-to/|title=Tariffs on China don't hurt Americans? Pants on Fire|website=@politifact}}</ref>\n\n=== Border adjustment tax ===\nNavarro supports a tax policy called \"border adjustment\", which, as commonly used in the [[value added taxes|VATs]] of most countries, taxes all imports at the domestic rate while rebating tax on exports, essentially transforming taxes from taxes on production to taxes on consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to criticism that the border adjustment tax could hurt U.S. companies and put jobs at risk, Navarro called it \"fake news.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Criticism of China ===\nAccording to ''Politico'', \"Navarro is perhaps the most extreme advocate in Washington, and maybe in all of economics, for an aggressive stance toward China.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Navarro put his attention to China in the mid-2000s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/13/peter-navarro-profile-national-trade-council-donald-trump-china-expert/ |title=Trump's Top China Expert Isn't a China Expert|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> His first publication on the subject is the 2006 book ''[[The Coming China Wars: Where They Will Be Fought, How They Can Be Won]]''.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/peter-navarro-trump-trade-china-214772 |title=The Most Dangerous Man in Trump World?|work=Politico|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Navarro has said that he started to examine China when he noticed that his former students were losing jobs, concluding that China was at fault.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn ''Politico''{{'}}s description of the book, \"Navarro uses military language to refer to China's trade policies, referring to its 'conquest' of the world's export markets, which has 'vaporized literally millions of manufacturing jobs and driven down wages.' ... China's aspirations are so insatiable, he claims, that eventually there will be a clash over \"our most basic of all needs\u2014bread, water, and air.'\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Navarro has described the entry of China to the World Trade Organization as one of the United States' biggest mistakes.<ref name=\":8\" /> To respond to the Chinese threat, Navarro has advocated for 43% tariffs, the repudiation of trade pacts, major increases in military expenditures and strengthened military ties with Taiwan.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"a wide range of economists have warned that curtailing trade with China would damage the American economy, forcing consumers to pay higher prices for goods and services.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/21/us/politics/peter-navarro-carl-icahn-trump-china-trade.html|title=Trump Taps Peter Navarro, Vocal Critic of China, for New Trade Post|last=Appelbaum|first=Binyamin|date=December 21, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Navarro has reportedly also encouraged President Trump to enact a 25-percent tariff on Chinese steel imports, something that \"trade experts worry... would upend global trade practices and cause countries to retaliate, potentially leading to a trade war\".<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\nNavarro has said that a large part of China's competitive advantage over the United States stems from unfair trade practices.<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro has criticized China for pollution, poor labor standards, government subsidies, producing \"contaminated, defective and cancerous\" exports, currency manipulation, and theft of US intellectual property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-06/u-s-aims-to-reclaim-global-supply-chain-trump-trade-aide-says|title=U.S. Will Reclaim Global Supply Chain, Trump Trade Aide Says|date=March 6, 2017|publisher=Bloomberg|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In his 2012 documentary, Navarro said that China caused the loss of 57,000 US factories and 25 million jobs. Navarro maintains that China manipulates its currency, and although most economists believe that it is not the case, the U.S. Treasury officially designated China as a \"Currency Manipulator\" on August 5th, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm751|title=Treasury Designates China as a Currency Manipulator {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOf the more than dozen China specialists contacted by ''Foreign Policy'', most either did not know of him or only interacted with him briefly.<ref name=\":8\" /> Kenneth Pomeranz, University of Chicago professor of Chinese History, said that his \"recollection is that [Navarro] generally avoided people who actually knew something about the country.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> Columnist [[Gordon G. Chang]] was the only China watcher contacted by ''Foreign Policy'' who defended Navarro, but even then noted that he disagreed with Navarro's claims of currency manipulation, opposition to the TPP and calls for high tariffs.<ref name=\":8\" /> James McGregor, a former chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in China, said that Navarro's books and documentary on China \"have close to zero credibility with people who know the country,\" and are filled with \"hyperbole, inaccuracies\" and a \"cartoonish caricature of China that he puts out.\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nSome of Navarro's views on China fit within the mainstream, such as criticism of Chinese currency manipulation (pre-2015), concern that China\u2019s rapid ascension to the World Trade Organization harmed the Rust Belt, and criticism of China's weak environmental regulations and poor labor standards.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Ron Vara ===\nIn six of his books about China, Navarro quotes a \"Ron Vara\", whom he describes as a China hawk and former Harvard PhD doctoral student in economics, and who says crass Sinophobic things about China and the Chinese. An investigation by the ''Chronicle'' found that this [[Author surrogate|character]] was made up, and that Ron Vara (an anagram of Navarro) appeared to represent views that Navarro himself held.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/20191015-navarro|title=Trump's 'China Muse' Has an Imaginary Friend|date=2019-10-15|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horsley |first1=Scott |title=White House Adviser Peter Navarro Calls Fictional Alter Ego An 'Inside Joke' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/18/771396016/white-house-adviser-peter-navarro-calls-fictional-alter-ego-an-inside-joke |website=npr |publisher=National Public Radio |accessdate=19 October 2019 |quote=\"As she put it, the joke wears very thin when you get to certain statements about China and the Chinese people that are quite negative,\" Bartlett said. \"Ron Vara says things that are pretty over the top, and it's hard to construe them necessarily as whimsical in the way we normally use that word.\"}}</ref> Navarro has admitted to making up the character and quoting him in his books. Economist [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]], who co-authored ''Seeds of Destruction'' with Navarro,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crook |first1=Clive |title=Hubbard and Navarro on the 'Seeds of Destruction' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2010/11/hubbard-and-navarro-on-the-seeds-of-destruction/66167/ |website=The Atlantic |publisher=The Atlantic |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> has said he was not aware that Vara was fictional and that he was not okay with it. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Arciga |first1=Julia |title=Trump Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Admits to Quoting Character He Invented in His Books |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-admits-to-quoting-character-he-invented-in-his-books |website=Daily Beast |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, a memo apparently authored by Ron Vara began circulating in Washington DC. The memo highlighted the \"Keep Tariff Argument\" and the use of tariffs against China a few days before an additional 15% tariff on $160 billion of Chinese made goods was set to be implemented. Navarro later confirmed that he had written the memo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/11/peter-navarros-alter-ego-ron-vara-shares-pro-tariff-memo-amid-trade-talks.html|title=Peter Navarro's alter ego 'Ron Vara' shares pro-tariff memo amid US-China trade talks|author=|date=December 11, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\nNavarro drew controversy when he accused Germany of using a \"grossly undervalued\" euro to \"exploit\" the US and the rest of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/57f104d2-e742-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> ''Politico'' noted that the German government does not set the value of the euro.<ref name=\":7\" /> Economists and commentators are divided on the accuracy of Navarro's remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2017/02/is-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=Is Germany a currency manipulator? |publisher=Bruegel|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/485bace6-ea0a-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said that Navarro was right and wrong at the same time: \"Yes, Germany in effect has an undervalued currency relative to what it would have without the euro... But does this mean that the euro as a whole is undervalued against the dollar? Probably not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/02/01/germany-the-euro-and-currency-manipulation/|title=Germany, the Euro, and Currency Manipulation|website=Paul Krugman Blog|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Boston University economist [[Laurence Kotlikoff]] described Navarro's accusation of Germany as a currency manipulator as \"#stupideconomics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kotlikoff/2017/02/01/the-latest-stupideconomics-peter-navarro-calls-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=The Latest #StupidEconomics \u2013 Peter Navarro Calls Germany A 'Currency Manipulator'|last=Kotlikoff|first=Laurence|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nNavarro argues that the decline in US manufacturing jobs is chiefly due to \"unfair trade practices and bad trade deals. And if you don't believe that, just go to the booming factories in Germany, in Japan, in Korea, in China, in Malaysia, in Vietnam, in Indonesia, in Italy\u2014every place that we're running deficits with.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/03/526621048/peter-navarro-a-bricklayer-of-trumps-protectionist-wall|title=Peter Navarro: A 'Bricklayer' Of Trump's Protectionist Wall |publisher=NPR|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> However, many economists attribute the decline in manufacturing jobs chiefly to [[automation]] and other innovations that allow manufacturing firms to produce more goods with fewer workers, rather than trade.<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/27/news/economy/donald-trump-economy/index.html|title=Trump will grow the economy like Reagan, says adviser Peter Navarro|last=Long|first=Heather|date=June 27, 2016|website=CNN Money|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNavarro has been a proponent of strengthening the manufacturing sector's role in the national economy: \"We envision a more Germany-style economy, where 20 percent of our workforce is in manufacturing. ... And we're not talking about banging tin in the back room.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"experts on manufacturing ... doubt that the government can significantly increase factory employment, noting that mechanization is the major reason fewer people are working in factories.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Opposition to NAFTA ===\nNavarro has called for the United States to leave the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and has tried to convince President Trump to initiate a withdrawal.<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\n=== Repatriation of global supply chains ===\nNavarro has called for repatriating global supply chains.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> According to ''Politico'''s [[Jacob Heilbrunn]], such a move \"would be enormously costly and take years to execute\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Trade as a national security risk ===\nNavarro has framed trade as a national security risk.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-makes-cutting-trade-deficit-top-priority-1488815842|title=Trump Adviser Peter Navarro: Trade Deficits Endanger U.S. National Security|last=Timiraos|first=Nick|date=March 6, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nNavarro has characterized foreign purchases of U.S. companies as a threat to national security, but according to NPR, this is \"a fringe view that puts him at odds with the vast majority of economists.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/03/10/519488848/trump-advisers-warning-about-food-supply-takeover-met-with-skepticism|title=Trump Adviser's Warning About Food Supply Takeover Met With Skepticism|last=|first=|date=|work=NPR.org|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en|quote=Peter Navarro says foreign companies buying up U.S. corporations are posing a threat to national security.}}</ref> Dartmouth economist Douglas Irwin noted that the US government already reviews foreign purchases of companies with military or strategic value, and has on occasion rejected such deals.<ref name=\":2\" /> Irwin said that Navarro had not substantiated his claim with any evidence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro has also said that the United States has \"already begun to lose control of [its] food supply chain\", which according to NPR, \"sounded pretty off-the-wall to a number of economists\" who noted that the US is a massive exporter of food.<ref name=\":2\" /> Dermot Hayes, an agribusiness economist at Iowa State University, described Navarro's statement as \"uninformed\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro criticized the [[outsourcing]] of critical materials \u2014 like the production of essential [[Medical device|medical supplies]] \u2014 to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade deficits ===\n{{main|Balance of trade}}\nNavarro is a proponent of the notion that [[trade deficit]]s are bad in and of themselves, a view which is widely rejected by trade experts and economists.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/06/economists-take-aim-at-trump-trade-theory-again-peter-navarro-bilateral-multilateral-trade-deals-china-germany-national-security/ |title=Economists Take Aim at Trump Trade Theory \u2013 Again |first=Robbie |last=Gramer |website=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's comments drew skepticism from trade experts and economists across the political spectrum\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro and Ross say that getting rid of the trade deficit and boosting investment would also spur faster economic growth, which would bring in $1.74 trillion in tax revenue over a decade.\"}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/03/07/trump-rails-against-the-trade-deficit-but-economists-say-theres-no-easy-way-for-him-to-make-it-go-away/|title=Analysis {{!}} Trump rails against trade deficit, but economists say there's no easy way for him to make it go away|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In a white paper co-authored with Wilbur Ross, Navarro stated, \"when a country runs a trade deficit by importing more than it exports, this subtracts from growth.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/navarros-trade-views-misguided-dangerous|title=Navarro's Trade Views 'Misguided', 'Dangerous'|date=December 23, 2016|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref> In a ''Wall Street Journal'' op-ed defending his views, Navarro stated, \"If we are able to reduce our trade deficits through tough, smart negotiations, we should be able to increase our growth.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-white-house-worries-about-trade-deficits-1488751930|title=Why the White House Worries About Trade Deficits|last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=March 5, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Harvard University economics professor [[Greg Mankiw|Gregory Mankiw]] has said that Navarro's views on the trade deficit are based on the kind of mistakes that \"even a freshman at the end of ec 10 knows.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2016/09/trumponomics.html|title=Greg Mankiw's Blog: Trumponomics|last=|first=|date=|website=gregmankiw.blogspot.com|language=en|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> Tufts University professor [[Daniel W. Drezner]] said about Navarro's op-ed, \"as someone who's written on this topic I could not for the life of me understand his reasoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2017/03/09/why-the-trump-administration-hates-multilateral-trade-agreements-the-most/|title=Perspective {{!}} Why the Trump administration hates multilateral trade agreements the most|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> According to [[Tyler Cowen]], \"close to no one\" in the economics profession agrees with Navarro's idea that a trade deficit is bad in and of itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208134200/http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archivedate=2016-12-08|title=What You Should Know About the Professor Who Has Trump's Ear on the Economy |publisher= The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 8, 2016|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> Nobel laureate [[Angus Deaton]] described Navarro's attitude on trade deficits as \"an old-fashioned mercantilist position.\"<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' magazine has described Navarro's views on the trade deficit as \"dodgy economics\",<ref name=\":0\" /> while the ''Financial Times'' has described them as \"poor economics\".<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eea50292-0331-11e7-aa5b-6bb07f5c8e12|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Economists Noah Smith,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-12-28/trump-s-trade-chief-peter-navarro-makes-a-rookie-mistake|title=Trump's Trade Chief Makes a Rookie Mistake|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=December 28, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Sumner]], [[Olivier Blanchard]],<ref name=\":10\" /> and Phil Levy<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/phillevy/2017/03/06/white-house-whiffs-on-trade-deficit-defense/#7aea21f06b6c|title=White House Whiffs On Trade Deficit Defense|last=Levy |first=Phil|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> have also criticized Navarro's views on the trade deficit. Dan Ikenson, director of the [[Cato Institute]]'s Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies goes so far as to call Navarro a \"charlatan\" and says that \"99.9 per cent of respectable economists would eschew\" what he says: \"He says imports deduct from output, and he calls that accounting identity the 'economic growth formula'. He thinks that for every dollar we import, our GDP is reduced by a dollar. I don't know how he got his PhD at Harvard.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=The purge of April: Trump's new advisers pour on the gas |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/the-purge-of-april-trump-s-new-advisers-pour-on-the-gas-1.4705201 |website=www.cbc.ca |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to Trans-Pacific Partnership ===\nNavarro opposes the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/238473-parsing-the-trans-pacific-partnership-agreement|title=Parsing the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=April 13, 2015|work=The Hill|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In an April 2015 op-ed, Navarro said, \"To woo us, their spinmeisters boast the TPP will spur American exports to stimulate sorely needed economic growth. In truth, the American economy will suffer severely. This is because the TPP will hammer two main drivers of economic growth\u2014domestic investment and 'net exports.'\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Navarro said in March 2017 that TPP \"would have been a \"death knell\" to America's auto and vehicle parts industry that we \"urgently need to bring back to full life.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> ''Politico''<nowiki/>'s Jacob Heilbrunn and ''the'' ''Economist'' argue that there may be a disconnect between Navarro's policy on China and his opposition to the TPP, as scuttling the TPP will strengthen China's hand.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Library resources box|about=no|by=yes}}\n\n* ''Crouching Tiger: What China's Militarism Means for the World'' (2015)\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBe2wpZqN0s Episode 1: Will There Be War With China?]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUA_wh88fYc Episode 2: The World At the Tip of a Chinese Spear]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odiv79hZhB4 Episode 3: The Wild Card of North Korea]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HEjlcmfNt3Y Episode 4: The Unsinkable Aircraft Carrier of Taiwan]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1csrTOxJ8JM Episode 5: Will There Be War Between China and Japan?]\n* ''[[Death by China (book)|Death by China: Confronting the Dragon \u2013 A Global Call to Action]]'' (2011)\n* ''Seeds of Destruction'' (with [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]]) (2010)\n* ''Always a Winner: Finding Your Competitive Advantage in an Up and Down Economy'' (2009)\n* ''The Well-Timed Strategy: Managing the Business Cycle for Competitive Advantage'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' (2006)\n* ''What the Best MBAs Know'' (2005)\n* ''Principles of Economics: Business, Banking, Finance, and Your Everyday Life'' (2005)\n* ''When the Market Moves, Will You Be Ready?'' (2003)\n* ''If It's Raining in Brazil, Buy Starbucks''<ref name=ISBN /> (2001)\n* ''Bill Clinton's Agenda for America'' (1993)\n* ''Job Opportunities Under Clinton/Gore'' (with Craig Adams) (1993)\n* ''The Policy Game'' (1984)\n* ''The Dimming of America: The Real Costs of Electric Utility Regulation'' (1984)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"PMSB-Awards\">{{cite web|title=Teaching Awards|url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|publisher=The Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826230801/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|archivedate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BP-CA49\">{{cite web|title=California's 49th Congressional District Elections|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California%27s_49th_Congressional_District|publisher=Ballotpedia|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-M\">{{cite web|title=Election Results \u2013 Mayor, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/mayorresults.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CSD-CD6\">{{cite web|title=Election History \u2013 Council District 6, City of San Diego|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/city-clerk/pdf/cd6results.pdf|publisher=City of San Diego|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ISBN\">{{cite web|title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Books|url=http://www.isbnsearch.org/search?s=peter+navarro|publisher=ISBN Search|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Peter Navarro}}\n* [http://www.peternavarro.com/ Official site]\n* {{C-SPAN|Peter Navarro 02}}\n* [http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589 UCI Faculty Profile]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2304583/ Death by China] at [[IMDb]]\n\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Navarro, Peter}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American economics writers]]\n[[Category:Economists from California]]\n[[Category:Economists from Florida]]\n[[Category:Economists from Maryland]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Peace Corps volunteers]]\n[[Category:People from Bethesda, Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Palm Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Irvine faculty]]\n[[Category:Bethesda-Chevy Chase High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Economist and member of the Trump administration}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter Navarro\n| image = Peter Navarro official photo.jpg\n| office = Director of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = April 29, 2017\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor =\n| office1 = Director of the [[National Trade Council]]\n| president1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start1 = January 20, 2017\n| term_end1 = April 29, 2017\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1 = Office dissolved\n|birth_name=Peter Kent Navarro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|7|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Peter Kent Navarro''' (born July 15, 1949) is an American economist and author. He serves in the Trump administration as the Assistant to the President, Director of Trade and Manufacturing Policy, and the national [[Defense Production Act]] policy coordinator. He previously served as a Deputy Assistant to the President and Director of the [[White House National Trade Council]], a newly created entity in the [[Executive Branch of the United States|executive branch]] of the U.S. government, until it was folded into the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], a new role established by executive order in April 2017.<ref name=\"joshwapo\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> He is also a professor emeritus of [[economics]] and [[public policy]] at the [[Paul Merage School of Business]], [[University of California, Irvine]], and the author of ''[[Death by China]].''<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nNavarro's views on trade are significantly outside the mainstream of economic thought, and are widely considered fringe and misguided by other economists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/02/trump-s-cabinet The wonkless White House], ''Economist'' (February 2017): \"Mr Navarro's views on trade are well outside the mainstream, and he is not a big hitter in academic circles.\"</ref><ref name=\"Coy\">Peter Coy, [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-08/after-defeating-cohn-trump-s-trade-warrior-is-on-the-rise-again After Defeating Cohn, Trump's Trade Warrior Is on the Rise Again], Bloomberg (March 8, 2018): \"Navarro has come a long way from his roots as a mainstream economist.\"</ref> A strong proponent of reducing [[U.S. trade deficit]]s, Navarro is well known as a critic of Germany and China and has accused both nations of currency manipulation.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\">{{cite magazine |last1=Lowrey |first1=Annie |title=The 'Madman' Behind Trump's Trade Theory |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/peter-navarro-trump-trade/573913/ |date=December 2018 |magazine=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018}}</ref> He has called for increasing the size of the [[manufacturing in the United States|American manufacturing sector]], setting high tariffs, and \"repatriating global supply chains\". He is also a strong opponent of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nNavarro was born on July 15, 1949, in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1996/candidates/election.guide/text/CA49.shtml|title=AllPolitics \u2013 Congressional Races \u2013 California District 49|website=www.cnn.com}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{cite magazine |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |title=Peter Navarro Used To Be a Democrat. Now He's the Mastermind Behind Trump's Trade War |url=http://time.com/5375727/peter-navarro/ |date=August 23, 2018 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Navarro's father, Alfred \"Al\" Navarro, a saxophonist and clarinetist, led a [[house band]], which played summers in [[New Hampshire]] and winters in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99097793/|title=Orchestra Leader is Dead from Detroit, Michigan on January 2, 1972 \u00b7 Page 32|newspaper= Detroit Free Press |accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was 9 or 10.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-05-02/trump-s-trade-warrior-is-the-most-unpopular-economist-in-the-class|title=Trump's Trade Warrior Is the Most Unpopular Economist in the Class|date=May 2, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>  Subsequently, he lived with his mother, Evelyn Littlejohn, a [[Saks Fifth Avenue]] secretary, in [[Palm Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\":17\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-08/local/me-4514_1_peter-navarro|title=Navarro Says Loan for Race Was Inherited: Mayoral candidate admits $300,000 was given to him by his mother, but all the money has been spent|first=Leonard|last=Bernstein|date=August 8, 1992|newspaper=LA Times|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> He lived in [[Bethesda, Maryland]] in a one-bedroom apartment with his mother and brother during his teenage years.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nNavarro went to [[Tufts University]] on a full academic scholarship,<ref name=\":23\" /> graduating in 1972 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He then spent three years in the [[Peace Corps|U.S. Peace Corps]], serving in Thailand.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\"cv\" /> He earned a [[Master of Public Administration]] from [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in 1979, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Economics]] from Harvard under the supervision of [[Richard E. Caves]] in 1986.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web |url=https://merage.uci.edu/_files/documents/faculty-profiles/Navarro-Peter-CV.pdf|title= Peter Navarro Curriculum Vitae |last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=August 2016|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Policy analysis===\nNavarro's policy prescriptions include that \"U.S. should be tough on trade, crack down on intellectual property theft, tax Chinese exports, combat Chinese mercantilism, [and] bring jobs home.\"<ref name=ct />\n\n===Academic career===\nFrom 1981 through 1985, he was a research associate at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]'s Energy and Environmental Policy Center. From 1985 through 1988, he taught at the [[University of California, San Diego]] and the [[University of San Diego]].<ref name = UT>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-peter-navarro-tariffs-san-diego-20180306-htmlstory.html |title=Former San Diego politician Peter Navarro is fighting for Trump's tariffs|last=Hamblin|first=Abby|date=March 6, 2018|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> In 1989 he moved to the [[University of California, Irvine]] as a professor of economics and public policy. He continued on the UC Irvine faculty for more than 20 years and is now a professor emeritus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://merage.uci.edu/research-faculty/faculty-directory/Peter-Navarro.html|title=Faculty Directory|website=UCI Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He has worked on energy issues and the relationship between the United States and [[Asia]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|title=Peter Navarro Bio |last=Navarro |first=Peter|website=The Paul Merage School of Business|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=January 6, 2017 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103004035/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/FacultyDirectory/FacultyProfiles.aspx?FacultyID=1589&Page=2|archivedate=January 3, 2017}}</ref> He has received multiple teaching awards for [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] courses he has taught.<ref name=PMSB-Awards />\n\nAs a doctoral student in 1984, Navarro wrote a book entitled ''The Policy Game: How Special Interests and Ideologues are Stealing America'', which discussed that special interest groups had led the United States to \"a point in its history where it cannot grow and prosper.\" In the book he also called for greater worker's compensation to help those who had lost jobs to trade and foreign competition. His doctoral thesis on why corporations donate to charity is one of his most highly-cited works. He has also done research in the topic of wind energy with Frank Harris, a former student of his.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Publications===\nNavarro is a prolific author with over a dozen books written on various topics in economics and specializing in issues of balance of trade. He has published peer-reviewed economics research on energy policy, charity, deregulation and the economics of trash collection.<ref name=\"ct\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-08-01/peter-navarro-is-the-economist-whose-ideas-guide-trump|title=Here's the Economist Whose Ideas Guide Trump|last=Cowen|first=Tyler|author-link=Tyler Cowen|date=August 1, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Navarro \u2013 Google Scholar Citations |url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=usrEMP4AAAAJ&hl=en |website=scholar.google.com |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Navarro \"is a prolific writer, but has no publications in top-tier academic journals... [although] his research interests are broader than the average economist\u2019s.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/briefing/2017/01/21/peter-navarro-is-about-to-become-one-of-the-worlds-most-powerful-economists|title=Peter Navarro is about to become one of the world's most powerful economists|journal=The Economist|access-date=December 8, 2018|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' is a book published by [[Financial Times|FT Press]] in (2006). Navarro examines China as an emerging [[world power]] confronting challenges at home and abroad as it struggles to exert itself in the [[economic globalization|global market]]. He also discusses how China's role in international commerce is creating conflicts with nations around the world over energy, natural resources, the environment, [[intellectual property]], and other issues. A review in ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' describes the book as \"comprehensive\" and \"contemporary\" and concludes that it \"will teach readers to understand the dragon, just not how to vanquish it\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6386391.html?q=The+Coming+China+Wars ''Publishers Weekly review of The Coming China Wars], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', October 30, 2006</ref>\n\n[[File:Professor Peter Navarro of the Business School at University of California, Irvine talks his work \"Death by China\" and how China cheats in the world trade system @ University of Michigan-4.jpg|thumb|Professor Peter Navarro discusses his work, ''[[Death by China]]'', arguing China cheats in the world trade system at [[University of Michigan]] in 2012]]\n''[[Death by China]]'' (2011) is a book by Navarro and Greg Autry. According to ''The Economist'', \"the core allegations Mr. Navarro makes against China are not all that controversial. He accuses China of keeping its currency cheap . . . He deplores China\u2019s practice of forcing American firms to hand over intellectual property as a condition of access to its market. He notes, correctly, that Chinese firms pollute the environment more freely and employ workers in far worse conditions than American rules allow.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro argues that China violates fair trade by \"illegal export subsidies and currency manipulation, effectively flooding the U.S. markets\" and unfairly making it \"virtually impossible\" for American companies to compete.<ref name=rs>{{cite web|title=Review: 'Death by China' |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948072?refcatid=31|website=Variety|author=Ronnie Scheib|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> It is a critique of \"global capitalism\" including foreign labor practices and environmental protection.<ref name=\"Salon\">Andrew O'Hehir, [http://www.salon.com/2012/08/22/chinas_not_so_secret_plan_for_world_domination/ \"China\u2019s not-so-secret plan for world domination\"], ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'', August 21, 2012.</ref> Currency manipulation and subsidies are stated as reasons that \"American companies cannot compete because they're not competing with Chinese companies, they're competing with the Chinese government.\"<ref name=ng>[[Neil Genzlinger]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/24/movies/death-by-china-documentary-directed-by-peter-navarro.html \"Casting Blame for Jobs That Vanish\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 23, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Navarro directed and produced a [[documentary film]] based on his book, ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perkins |first1=Olivera |title=Economist Peter Navarro says U.S. manufacturing is suffering 'Death by China' |url=http://www.cleveland.com/business/index.ssf/2012/09/film_says_us_manufacturing_is.html|website=The Cleveland Plain Dealer |accessdate=January 19, 2017|date=September 7, 2012}}</ref> The film, described as \"fervently anti-China\",<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Katie|last=Quan|year=2017|title=Prospects for US-China Union Relations in the Era of Xi and Trump|journal=International Union Rights|page=13|volume=24|issue=4|doi=10.14213/inteuniorigh.24.4.0011 }}</ref> was released under the same title and narrated by [[Martin Sheen]]. From 2011 until 2016, Navarro was a frequent guest on the radio program the John Batchelor Show.\n\n===Political career===\n\n====Politics and campaigns for public office====\nWhile teaching at UC Irvine, Navarro ran unsuccessfully for office in [[San Diego, California]] five times.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name = UT/> In 1992, he [[San Diego mayoral election, 1992|ran for mayor]], finishing first (38.2%) in the primary, but lost with 48% to [[Susan Golding]] in the runoff.<ref name=CSD-M /> During his mayoral campaign, Navarro ran on a no-growth platform.<ref name=\"SanDiegoSprawl\">{{Cite book|title=The Failure of Planning: Permitting Sprawl in San Diego Suburbs, 1970\u20131999|last=Hogan|first=Richard|publisher=[[Ohio State University Press]]|year=2002|isbn=978-0814251041|location=United States|page=[https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119 119]|url=https://archive.org/details/failureofplannin0000hoga/page/119}}</ref> In 1993, he ran for San Diego city council and in 1994 for San Diego County board of supervisors.<ref name = UT/> In 1996, he ran for the [[California's 49th congressional district|49th Congressional District]] as the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee, but lost to Republican [[Brian Bilbray]], 52.7% to 41.9%.<ref name=BP-CA49 /> In 2001, Navarro ran in a special election to fill the District 6 San Diego city council seat, but lost in a special election with 7.85% of the vote.<ref name=CSD-CD6 />\n\nNavarro supported President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[phase-out of incandescent light bulbs]], the adoption of [[Wind power|wind energy]], and [[carbon tax]]es in order to stop [[global warming]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/a-pit-bull-for-climate-could-soon-sit-next-to-trump/|title=A \"Pit Bull\" for Climate Could Soon Sit Next to Trump|last=News|first=Robin Bravender,Zack Colman,E&E|work=Scientific American|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Trump campaign advisor ====\nIn 2016, Navarro served as an economic policy adviser to Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"appoint\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/greatagain/navarro-national-trade-council-c2d90c10eacb|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Appoints Dr. Peter Navarro to Head the White House National Trade Council|first=The Transition|last=Team|date=December 21, 2016|website=Medium}}</ref> He advocated for an [[Isolationism|isolationist]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] American foreign policy.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|title=White House At A Crossroads After Cohn|last=Soergel|first=Andrew|date=March 7, 2018|website=US News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308014013/https://www.usnews.com/news/economy/articles/2018-03-07/white-house-at-a-crossroads-after-cohn|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Navarro and the international private equity investor [[Wilbur Ross]] authored an economic plan for Trump campaign in September 2016.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan|title=New White Paper on Donald J. Trump's Economic Plan |website=www.donaldjtrump.com|access-date=March 6, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045918/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/white-paper-on-djt-econ-plan |archivedate=March 8, 2017}}</ref> Navarro was invited to be an adviser after [[Jared Kushner]], while he was researching China for Trump, saw on Amazon that Navarro co-wrote ''[[Death by China]]''.<ref name=\"Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon\">{{cite web|last1=Vladimirov|first1=Nikita|title=Report: Kushner found Trump advisor Navarro by browsing Amazon |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/328969-report-kushner-found-trump-economic-advisor-navarro-by-browsing|website=TheHill|accessdate=April 18, 2017|language=English|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> When told that the [[Tax Policy Center]] assessment of Trump's economic plan would reduce federal revenues by $6 trillion and reduce economic growth in the long term, Navarro said that the analysis demonstrated \"a high degree of analytical and political malfeasance\".<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/10/24/trumps-advisers-see-another-conspiracy-far-from-the-campaign-trail/|title=Trump's advisers see another conspiracy \u2013 far from the campaign trail|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> When the Peterson Institute for International Affairs estimated that Trump's economic plan would cost millions of Americans their jobs, Navarro said that writers at the Peterson Institute \"weave a false narrative and they come up with some phony numbers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2016/09/19/trump-adviser-bullish-wake-tax-trade-critiques/ |title=Trump Adviser Bullish in Wake of Tax, Trade Critiques|last=Rainey|first=Ryan|date=September 19, 2016|website=Morning Consult |access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> According to MIT economist [[Simon Johnson (economist)|Simon Johnson]], the economic plan essay authored by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Donald Trump during the campaign had projections \"based on assumptions so unrealistic that they seem to have come from a different planet. If the United States really did adopt Trump's plan, the result would be an immediate and unmitigated disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/trump-insane-economic-plan-by-simon-johnson-2016-09?barrier=accessreg|title=Trump's Magical Economic Thinking|last=Johnson|first=Simon|date=September 30, 2016 |work=Project Syndicate|access-date=March 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When 370 economists, including nineteen Nobel laureates, signed a letter warning against Donald Trump's stated economic policies in November 2016, Navarro said that the letter was \"an embarrassment to the corporate offshoring wing of the economist profession who continues to insist bad trade deals are good for America.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-of-prominent-us-economists-warn-against-voting-trump/|title=Hundreds of US economists warn against voting Trump|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, with [[Wilbur Ross]] and [[Andy Puzder]], Navarro co-authored the essay titled \"Economic Analysis of Donald Trump's Contract with the American Voter\".<ref>[[Wilbur Ross]], [[Andy Puzder]] & Peter Navarro, [http://www.publicnow.com/view/26F924AB8FA783A28FEA3EE8943635B4F0574556?2016-10-31-14:32:09+00:00-xxx4035]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald J. Trump for President, Inc.]], October 30, 2016</ref>\n\n====White House trade advisor====\n[[File:Peter Navarro, Director of the White House National Trade Council, Addresses in the Oval Office before U.S. President Donald Trump Signs Executive Orders Regarding Trade on March 31, 2017 4.jpg|thumb|Director Peter Navarro addresses President [[Donald Trump]]'s promises to American people, workers, and domestic manufacturers ('''[https://assets.donaldjtrump.com/DJT_DeclaringAmericanEconomicIndependence.pdf Declaring American Economic Independence]''' on June 28, 2016) in the [[Oval Office]] with [[U.S. Vice President|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] and [[Secretary of Commerce]] [[Wilbur Ross]] before President Trump signs [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Orders]] regarding trade in March 2017<ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-regarding-omnibus-report-significant-trade Presidential Executive Order Regarding the Omnibus Report on Significant Trade Deficits], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/31/presidential-executive-order-establishing-enhanced-collection-and Presidential Executive Order on Establishing Enhanced Collection and Enforcement of Antidumping and Countervailing Duties and Violations of Trade and Customs Laws], [[White House]], March 31, 2016</ref>]]\nOn December 21, 2016, Navarro was selected by President-elect Trump to head a newly created position, as director of the [[White House National Trade Council]].<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title='Death by China' author to lead Trump trade office|url=https://www.ft.com/content/71a201d2-c7b3-11e6-8f29-9445cac8966f|website=www.ft.com|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> He outlines President Trump's trade policy as aiming to create jobs, revive the manufacturing sector, and improve the country's trade balance. He warned that trade deficits could jeopardize U.S. national security by allowing unfriendly nations to encroach on American supply chains. One of his main missions is to focus on behaviors by other countries that he considers abusive, cheating, illegal, and unfair against the U.S.<ref>[https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4659659/peter-navarro-outlines-trump-administration-trade-policy-priorities Peter Navarro Outlines Trump Administration Trade Policy Priorities], [[C-SPAN]], June 3, 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/videos/2017-03-31/navarro-says-not-all-trade-deficits-necessarily-bad-video Peter Navarro Says Trade Deficits Aren't Always Bad], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], March 31, 2017</ref>\n\n====Director of Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy====\nIn April 2017, the National Trade Council became part of the [[Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy]], of which Navarro was appointed Director.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news| last1=Cook | first1=Nancy | last2=Restuccia | first2=Andrew |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/peter-navarro-trump-trade-240611|title=Trump's trade warrior prowls the West Wing|date=July 17, 2017|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> By September 2017, the Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy had been folded into the National Economic Council, which meant that Navarro would report to NEC Director [[Gary Cohn (investment banker)|Gary Cohn]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/27/peter-navarro-trade-office-national-economic-council-243217|title=Kelly folds Navarro's trade shop into National Economic Council|work=Politico|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, several media outlets reported that Navarro's influence in the administration was rising again and that he would likely be promoted from the secondary billet of Deputy Assistant to the President to Assistant to the President, giving Navarro parity with the NEC Director.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Swanson | first1=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, a Top Trade Skeptic, Is Ascendant | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/25/us/politics/peter-navarro-trade.html | date=February 25, 2018 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Lynch | first1=David J. | last2=Damian | first2=Paletta | title=Trump Tilts Toward Hard-Liners Ahead of Key Trade Decisions | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/trump-tilts-toward-hard-liners-ahead-of-key-trade-decisions/2018/02/26/ffe93e46-1b32-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html | date=February 26, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Josh Rogin]], writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', reported that Navarro had used his prior time of lower influence to lead several low-profile policy items, such as working to increase military funding, drafting [[:s:Executive Order 13806|Executive Order 13806]], and leading the effort to solve a dispute between the United States and [[Qatar]] over the Open Skies Agreement between the two countries.<ref name=\"joshwapo\">{{cite news | last1=Rogin | first1=Josh | title=How Peter Navarro Got His Groove Back | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2018/02/27/how-peter-navarro-got-his-groove-back/ | date=February 27, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn explaining his role in the Trump administration, Navarro said that he is there to \"provide the underlying analytics that confirm [Trump's] intuition [on trade]. And his intuition is always right in these matters.\"<ref name=\"Coy\" />\n\nIn June 2018, Navarro said that there was \"a special place in hell\" for Justin Trudeau, the Prime Minister of Canada, after Trudeau said that Canada would respond with retaliatory tariffs since the United States had placed tariffs on Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/10/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Peter Navarro says 'there's a special place in hell' for Justin Trudeau|last= Watkins|first=Eli|work=CNN|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref> The Prime Minister's point-of-view and Canada's response to these tariffs were already public and well-known when Navarro made this comment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/white-house-adviser-kudlow-trump-trudeau-g7-summit-blame-1.4700061|title='Special place in hell': Trump advisers blast Trudeau for comments at G7 summit {{!}} CBC News|work=CBC|access-date=June 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>  Navarro later apologized.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/12/politics/peter-navarro-justin-trudeau/index.html|title=Navarro sorry after saying there's a 'special place in hell' for Trudeau|first=Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Navarro said that Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States as \"a brilliant move\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/31/mnuchin-and-lighthizer-were-opposed-to-trump-tariffs-on-mexico-source-says.html|title=Mnuchin and Lighthizer opposed Trump tariffs on Mexico, source says|last=Higgins|first=Kayla Tausche,Tucker|date=2019-05-31|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, after being tasked by the President to combat China's usage of international mail rates to more cheaply ship products into the US, Navarro successfully led a diplomatic effort to the third Extraordinary Congress of the [[Universal Postal Union]] where it agreed member countries could be able to opt-in to self-declare their rates starting in July 2020, after repeated threats from the Trump administration to leave the UPU unless global postage rates were changed so countries like China could no longer unfairly benefit from international delivery prices, particularly when it came to e-commerce deliveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/26/trump-scores-a-big-victory-on-stamps-postal-union-terminal-dues-china/|title=Trump Scores a Big Victory-on Stamps|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-un-postal/u-n-postal-union-clinches-deal-to-keep-u-s-in-club-idUSKBN1WA247|title=U.N. postal union clinches deal to keep U.S. in club|last= Nebehay|first=Stephanie|work=Reuters|date=September 25, 2019|access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNavarro continued to promote policies challenging amid trade negotiations between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Schlesinger | first1=Jacob M. | last2=Salama | first2=Vivian | title=New White House Report, Authored by Trade Hawk, Blasts Chinese 'Economic Aggression'  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-white-house-report-authored-by-trade-hawk-blasts-chinese-economic-aggression-1529456401 | date=June 19, 2018 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=In the Battles Over Trump's Trade Wars, Hawkish Adviser Navarro Endures  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-the-battles-over-trumps-trade-wars-hawkish-adviser-navarro-endures-11576943074 | date=December 21, 2019 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Rappeport | first1=Alan | last2=Swanson | first2=Ana | title=Peter Navarro, Trump's Trade Warrior, Has Not Made His Peace With China | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/26/us/politics/peter-navarro-china-trade.html | date=December 26, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNavarro worked with the DHS to initiate a crackdown on counterfeited and pirated e-commerce goods from overseas,<ref>{{cite web | last1=Shepardson | first1=David | title=U.S. to unveil crackdown on counterfeit, pirated e-commerce goods | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-counterfeiting/u-s-to-unveil-crackdown-on-counterfeit-pirated-e-commerce-goods-idUSKBN1ZN02E | date=January 23, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alan Rappeport |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/us/politics/us-cracks-down-on-counterfeits-in-a-warning-shot-to-china.html |title=U.S. Cracks Down on Counterfeits in a Warning Shot to China - The New York Times |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= January 24, 2020|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mauldin | first1=William | last2=Leary | first2=Alex | title=U.S. Signals Crackdown on Counterfeit Goods Sold Online  | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-signals-crackdown-on-counterfeit-goods-sold-online-11579820400 | date=January 24, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/24/dhs-report-targets-online-counterfeit-sales-on-amazon-e-commerce.html |title=DHS report targets online counterfeit sales on Amazon, e-commerce |publisher=Cnbc.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and he promoted the administration's actions on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jessica Bursztynsky |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/16/navarro-to-amazon-ebay-china-trade-deal-cracks-down-on-counterfeits.html |title=Navarro to Amazon, eBay: China trade deal cracks down on counterfeits |publisher=Cnbc.com |date=2020-01-16 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Navarro |first=Peter |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/perspectives/peter-navarro-e-commerce-counterfeit-products/index.html |title=Navarro: Counterfeits harm Americans and threaten national security. Trump has a plan to combat them (opinion) |publisher=CNN |date=2020-01-31 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> Trump signed an executive order on the matter on January 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web | title=Trump signs executive order aimed at preventing sales of counterfeit goods from overseas | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-shipments/trump-signs-executive-order-aimed-at-preventing-sales-of-counterfeit-goods-from-overseas-idUSKBN1ZU35P | date=January 31, 2020 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, it was reported that Navarro was conducting his own investigation into the identity of the author of [[I Am Part of the Resistance Inside the Trump Administration|an anonymous op-ed in ''The New York Times'']] criticizing the Trump Administration.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Suebsaeng | first1=Asawin | last2=Markay | first2=Lachlan | title=Trump's Top Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Has a Side Project: Secretly Hunting for 'Anonymous' | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-top-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-has-a-side-project-secretly-hunting-for-anonymous | date=February 17, 2020 | work=[[The Daily Beast]] | accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Infrastructure plan====\nDuring the campaign Navarro, together with [[Wilbur Ross]] who became Trump's [[Commerce Secretary]], designed a $1 trillion infrastructure development plan for Trump's presidential campaign.<ref name=\"peternavarro.com\">{{cite web|url=http://peternavarro.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/infrastructurereport.pdf|title=Infrastructure report|date=|publisher=peternavarro.com|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> The plan called for $137 billion in tax credits to private business to induce them to financing the bulk of infrastructure spending. Economists across the political spectrum derided the proposal.<ref name=\"Mufson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/economists-pan-infrastructure-plan-championed-by-trump-nominees/2017/01/17/0ed1ad5e-dc5e-11e6-918c-99ede3c8cafa_story.html|title=Economists pan infrastructure plan championed by Trump nominees|last=Mufson|first=Steven|date=January 17, 2017|via=www.washingtonpost.com|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> Trump released a $1.5 trillion version of this plan in February 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/infrastructure/373408-white-house-releases-55-page-infrastructure-proposal|title=White House releases 55-page, $1.5 trillion infrastructure plan|first=Mallory|last=Shelbourne|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref> but the Republican-controlled Congress showed little enthusiasm for the proposal, with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] reporting, \"President Trump's infrastructure plan appears to have crashed and burned in Congress\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/377681-trumps-infrastructure-push-hits-wall-in-congress|title=Trump's infrastructure push hits wall in Congress|first=Dustin|last=Weaver|date=March 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Navarro memo====\nOn January 29, 2020 Navarro issued a memo warning that coronavirus could \"evolv[e] into a full-blown pandemic, imperiling the lives of millions of Americans\" and that the \"risk of a worst-case pandemic scenario should not be overlooked\". He argued for restrictions on travel from China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trade Adviser Warned White House in January of Risks of a Pandemic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/us/politics/navarro-warning-trump-coronavirus.html?action=click&module=Spotlight&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n====National Defense Production Act policy coordinator====\nOn March 27, 2020, Trump appointed Navarro to coordinate the federal government's [[Defense Production Act]] policy response during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/489938-trump-names-new-defense-production-act-coordinator-for-coronavirus|title=Trump names new Defense Production Act coordinator for coronavirus fight|first=Morgan|last=Chalfant|date=March 27, 2020|publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Pappas | first1=Alex | title=Trump appoints Navarro to lead Defense Production Act efforts after forcing GM to make ventilators | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-aide-navarro-lead-defense-production-act-efforts | date=March 27, 2020 | work=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Leary | first1=Alex | title=\u2018This is War\u2019: President\u2019s Equipment Czar to Use Full Powers to Fight Coronavirus | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-is-war-presidents-equipment-czar-to-use-full-powers-to-fight-coronavirus-11585435836 | date=March 28, 2020 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Views on trade ==\n{{main|International trade|Commercial policy|Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign}}\nNavarro has been a staunch critic of trade with China and strong proponent of reducing U.S. trade deficits. He has attacked Germany, Japan and China for currency manipulation. He has called for increasing the size of the American manufacturing sector, setting high tariffs, and repatriating global supply chains. He was a fierce opponent of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]].\n\nAccording to [[Bloomberg News]], Navarro had \"roots as a mainstream economist\" as he voiced support for free trade in his 1984 book ''The Policy Game''. He changed his positions as he saw \"the globalist erosion of the American economy\" develop.<ref name=\"Coy\"/>\n\nAccording to ''Politico'', Navarro's economic theories are \"considered fringe\" by his fellow economists.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2017/03/trump-trade-attack-dog-peter-navarro-000353|title=Trump's attack dog on trade|last=|first=|date=|work=The Agenda|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> A ''New Yorker'' reporter described Navarro's views on trade and China as so radical \"that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/business/currency/trumps-muse-on-u-s-trade-with-china|title=Trump's Muse on U.S. Trade with China|last=|first=|date=October 12, 2016|website=The New Yorker|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's views on trade and China are so radical, however, that, even with his assistance, I was unable to find another economist who fully agrees with them.}}</ref> The ''Economist'' described Navarro as having \"oddball views\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21721937-donald-trumps-economic-strategy-unimaginative-and-incoherent-cooking-up-economic-policy|title=Cooking up an economic policy|website=The Economist|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> The George Mason University economist [[Tyler Cowen]] has described him as \"one of the most versatile and productive American economists of the last few decades\", but Cowen noted that he disagreed with his views on trade, which he claimed go \"against a strong professional consensus.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> University of Michigan economist [[Justin Wolfers]] described Navarro's views as \"far outside the mainstream,\" noting that \"he endorses few of the key tenets of\" the economics profession.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/upshot/why-most-economists-are-so-worried-about-trump.html|title=Why Most Economists Are So Worried About Trump|last=Wolfers|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|access-date=January 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331|quote=the only official who identifies as an economist\u2014Peter Navarro, who earned a Harvard Ph.D. in economics and will head up the newly formed National Trade Council\u2014stands so far outside the mainstream that he endorses few of the key tenets of the profession.|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> According to Lee Branstetter, economics professor at [[Carnegie Mellon University|Carnegie Mellon]] and trade expert with the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], Navarro \"was never a part of the group of economists who ever studied the global free-trade system ... He doesn't publish in journals. What he's writing and saying right now has nothing to do with what he got his Harvard Ph.D. in ... he doesn't do research that would meet the scientific standards of that community.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://businessinsider.com/what-is-trumpenomics-according-to-peter-navarro-2017-1|title=The clearest articulation of what Trump wants to do to America's economy comes from one person|last=|first=|date=|work=Business Insider|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Marcus Noland, an economist at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, described a tax and trade paper written by Navarro and Wilbur Ross for Trump as \"a complete misunderstanding of international trade, on their part.\"<ref name=\":82\"/>\n\nIn August 2019, Navarro asserted the tariffs of the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]] were not hurting Americans. Citing extensive evidence to the contrary, Politifact rated Navarro's assertion \"Pants on Fire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/aug/20/peter-navarro/donald-trumps-tariffs-china-dont-hurt-americans-to/|title=Tariffs on China don't hurt Americans? Pants on Fire|website=@politifact}}</ref>\n\n=== Border adjustment tax ===\nNavarro supports a tax policy called \"border adjustment\", which, as commonly used in the [[value added taxes|VATs]] of most countries, taxes all imports at the domestic rate while rebating tax on exports, essentially transforming taxes from taxes on production to taxes on consumption.<ref name=\":6\" /> In response to criticism that the border adjustment tax could hurt U.S. companies and put jobs at risk, Navarro called it \"fake news.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Criticism of China ===\nAccording to ''Politico'', \"Navarro is perhaps the most extreme advocate in Washington, and maybe in all of economics, for an aggressive stance toward China.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Navarro put his attention to China in the mid-2000s.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/13/peter-navarro-profile-national-trade-council-donald-trump-china-expert/ |title=Trump's Top China Expert Isn't a China Expert|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> His first publication on the subject is the 2006 book ''[[The Coming China Wars: Where They Will Be Fought, How They Can Be Won]]''.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/peter-navarro-trump-trade-china-214772 |title=The Most Dangerous Man in Trump World?|work=Politico|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Navarro has said that he started to examine China when he noticed that his former students were losing jobs, concluding that China was at fault.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn ''Politico''{{'}}s description of the book, \"Navarro uses military language to refer to China's trade policies, referring to its 'conquest' of the world's export markets, which has 'vaporized literally millions of manufacturing jobs and driven down wages.' ... China's aspirations are so insatiable, he claims, that eventually there will be a clash over \"our most basic of all needs\u2014bread, water, and air.'\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Navarro has described the entry of China to the World Trade Organization as one of the United States' biggest mistakes.<ref name=\":8\" /> To respond to the Chinese threat, Navarro has advocated for 43% tariffs, the repudiation of trade pacts, major increases in military expenditures and strengthened military ties with Taiwan.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"a wide range of economists have warned that curtailing trade with China would damage the American economy, forcing consumers to pay higher prices for goods and services.\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/21/us/politics/peter-navarro-carl-icahn-trump-china-trade.html|title=Trump Taps Peter Navarro, Vocal Critic of China, for New Trade Post|last=Appelbaum|first=Binyamin|date=December 21, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Navarro has reportedly also encouraged President Trump to enact a 25-percent tariff on Chinese steel imports, something that \"trade experts worry... would upend global trade practices and cause countries to retaliate, potentially leading to a trade war\".<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\nNavarro has said that a large part of China's competitive advantage over the United States stems from unfair trade practices.<ref name=\":0\" /> Navarro has criticized China for pollution, poor labor standards, government subsidies, producing \"contaminated, defective and cancerous\" exports, currency manipulation, and theft of US intellectual property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-06/u-s-aims-to-reclaim-global-supply-chain-trump-trade-aide-says|title=U.S. Will Reclaim Global Supply Chain, Trump Trade Aide Says|date=March 6, 2017|publisher=Bloomberg|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In his 2012 documentary, Navarro said that China caused the loss of 57,000 US factories and 25 million jobs. Navarro maintains that China manipulates its currency, and although most economists believe that it is not the case, the U.S. Treasury officially designated China as a \"Currency Manipulator\" on August 5th, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm751|title=Treasury Designates China as a Currency Manipulator {{!}} U.S. Department of the Treasury|website=home.treasury.gov|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOf the more than dozen China specialists contacted by ''Foreign Policy'', most either did not know of him or only interacted with him briefly.<ref name=\":8\" /> Kenneth Pomeranz, University of Chicago professor of Chinese History, said that his \"recollection is that [Navarro] generally avoided people who actually knew something about the country.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> Columnist [[Gordon G. Chang]] was the only China watcher contacted by ''Foreign Policy'' who defended Navarro, but even then noted that he disagreed with Navarro's claims of currency manipulation, opposition to the TPP and calls for high tariffs.<ref name=\":8\" /> James McGregor, a former chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in China, said that Navarro's books and documentary on China \"have close to zero credibility with people who know the country,\" and are filled with \"hyperbole, inaccuracies\" and a \"cartoonish caricature of China that he puts out.\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nSome of Navarro's views on China fit within the mainstream, such as criticism of Chinese currency manipulation (pre-2015), concern that China\u2019s rapid ascension to the World Trade Organization harmed the Rust Belt, and criticism of China's weak environmental regulations and poor labor standards.<ref name=\"Lowrey2018\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Ron Vara ===\nIn six of his books about China, Navarro quotes a \"Ron Vara\", whom he describes as a China hawk and former Harvard PhD doctoral student in economics, and who says crass Sinophobic things about China and the Chinese. An investigation by the ''Chronicle'' found that this [[Author surrogate|character]] was made up, and that Ron Vara (an anagram of Navarro) appeared to represent views that Navarro himself held.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/interactives/20191015-navarro|title=Trump's 'China Muse' Has an Imaginary Friend|date=2019-10-15|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horsley |first1=Scott |title=White House Adviser Peter Navarro Calls Fictional Alter Ego An 'Inside Joke' |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/18/771396016/white-house-adviser-peter-navarro-calls-fictional-alter-ego-an-inside-joke |website=npr |publisher=National Public Radio |accessdate=19 October 2019 |quote=\"As she put it, the joke wears very thin when you get to certain statements about China and the Chinese people that are quite negative,\" Bartlett said. \"Ron Vara says things that are pretty over the top, and it's hard to construe them necessarily as whimsical in the way we normally use that word.\"}}</ref> Navarro has admitted to making up the character and quoting him in his books. Economist [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]], who co-authored ''Seeds of Destruction'' with Navarro,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crook |first1=Clive |title=Hubbard and Navarro on the 'Seeds of Destruction' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2010/11/hubbard-and-navarro-on-the-seeds-of-destruction/66167/ |website=The Atlantic |publisher=The Atlantic |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> has said he was not aware that Vara was fictional and that he was not okay with it. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Arciga |first1=Julia |title=Trump Trade Adviser Peter Navarro Admits to Quoting Character He Invented in His Books |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-admits-to-quoting-character-he-invented-in-his-books |website=Daily Beast |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, a memo apparently authored by Ron Vara began circulating in Washington DC. The memo highlighted the \"Keep Tariff Argument\" and the use of tariffs against China a few days before an additional 15% tariff on $160 billion of Chinese made goods was set to be implemented. Navarro later confirmed that he had written the memo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/11/peter-navarros-alter-ego-ron-vara-shares-pro-tariff-memo-amid-trade-talks.html|title=Peter Navarro's alter ego 'Ron Vara' shares pro-tariff memo amid US-China trade talks|author=|date=December 11, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\nNavarro drew controversy when he accused Germany of using a \"grossly undervalued\" euro to \"exploit\" the US and the rest of the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/57f104d2-e742-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> ''Politico'' noted that the German government does not set the value of the euro.<ref name=\":7\" /> Economists and commentators are divided on the accuracy of Navarro's remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bruegel.org/2017/02/is-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=Is Germany a currency manipulator? |publisher=Bruegel|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/485bace6-ea0a-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] said that Navarro was right and wrong at the same time: \"Yes, Germany in effect has an undervalued currency relative to what it would have without the euro... But does this mean that the euro as a whole is undervalued against the dollar? Probably not.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/02/01/germany-the-euro-and-currency-manipulation/|title=Germany, the Euro, and Currency Manipulation|website=Paul Krugman Blog|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Boston University economist [[Laurence Kotlikoff]] described Navarro's accusation of Germany as a currency manipulator as \"#stupideconomics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kotlikoff/2017/02/01/the-latest-stupideconomics-peter-navarro-calls-germany-a-currency-manipulator/|title=The Latest #StupidEconomics \u2013 Peter Navarro Calls Germany A 'Currency Manipulator'|last=Kotlikoff|first=Laurence|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nNavarro argues that the decline in US manufacturing jobs is chiefly due to \"unfair trade practices and bad trade deals. And if you don't believe that, just go to the booming factories in Germany, in Japan, in Korea, in China, in Malaysia, in Vietnam, in Indonesia, in Italy\u2014every place that we're running deficits with.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/05/03/526621048/peter-navarro-a-bricklayer-of-trumps-protectionist-wall|title=Peter Navarro: A 'Bricklayer' Of Trump's Protectionist Wall |publisher=NPR|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref> However, many economists attribute the decline in manufacturing jobs chiefly to [[automation]] and other innovations that allow manufacturing firms to produce more goods with fewer workers, rather than trade.<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/06/27/news/economy/donald-trump-economy/index.html|title=Trump will grow the economy like Reagan, says adviser Peter Navarro|last=Long|first=Heather|date=June 27, 2016|website=CNN Money|access-date=May 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNavarro has been a proponent of strengthening the manufacturing sector's role in the national economy: \"We envision a more Germany-style economy, where 20 percent of our workforce is in manufacturing. ... And we're not talking about banging tin in the back room.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The New York Times'' notes that \"experts on manufacturing ... doubt that the government can significantly increase factory employment, noting that mechanization is the major reason fewer people are working in factories.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Opposition to NAFTA ===\nNavarro has called for the United States to leave the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] and has tried to convince President Trump to initiate a withdrawal.<ref name=\":20\"/>\n\n=== Repatriation of global supply chains ===\nNavarro has called for repatriating global supply chains.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> According to ''Politico'''s [[Jacob Heilbrunn]], such a move \"would be enormously costly and take years to execute\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Trade as a national security risk ===\nNavarro has framed trade as a national security risk.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trade-adviser-peter-navarro-makes-cutting-trade-deficit-top-priority-1488815842|title=Trump Adviser Peter Navarro: Trade Deficits Endanger U.S. National Security|last=Timiraos|first=Nick|date=March 6, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\nNavarro has characterized foreign purchases of U.S. companies as a threat to national security, but according to NPR, this is \"a fringe view that puts him at odds with the vast majority of economists.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2017/03/10/519488848/trump-advisers-warning-about-food-supply-takeover-met-with-skepticism|title=Trump Adviser's Warning About Food Supply Takeover Met With Skepticism|last=|first=|date=|work=NPR.org|access-date=March 12, 2017|language=en|quote=Peter Navarro says foreign companies buying up U.S. corporations are posing a threat to national security.}}</ref> Dartmouth economist Douglas Irwin noted that the US government already reviews foreign purchases of companies with military or strategic value, and has on occasion rejected such deals.<ref name=\":2\" /> Irwin said that Navarro had not substantiated his claim with any evidence.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro has also said that the United States has \"already begun to lose control of [its] food supply chain\", which according to NPR, \"sounded pretty off-the-wall to a number of economists\" who noted that the US is a massive exporter of food.<ref name=\":2\" /> Dermot Hayes, an agribusiness economist at Iowa State University, described Navarro's statement as \"uninformed\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNavarro criticized the [[outsourcing]] of critical materials \u2014 like the production of essential [[Medical device|medical supplies]] \u2014 to China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Break with China? Top Trump aide eyes an opening with coronavirus |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/26/trump-china-trade-coronavirus-117531 |work=Politico |date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade deficits ===\n{{main|Balance of trade}}\nNavarro is a proponent of the notion that [[trade deficit]]s are bad in and of themselves, a view which is widely rejected by trade experts and economists.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/06/economists-take-aim-at-trump-trade-theory-again-peter-navarro-bilateral-multilateral-trade-deals-china-germany-national-security/ |title=Economists Take Aim at Trump Trade Theory \u2013 Again |first=Robbie |last=Gramer |website=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro's comments drew skepticism from trade experts and economists across the political spectrum\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017|quote=Navarro and Ross say that getting rid of the trade deficit and boosting investment would also spur faster economic growth, which would bring in $1.74 trillion in tax revenue over a decade.\"}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/03/07/trump-rails-against-the-trade-deficit-but-economists-say-theres-no-easy-way-for-him-to-make-it-go-away/|title=Analysis {{!}} Trump rails against trade deficit, but economists say there's no easy way for him to make it go away|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In a white paper co-authored with Wilbur Ross, Navarro stated, \"when a country runs a trade deficit by importing more than it exports, this subtracts from growth.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/navarros-trade-views-misguided-dangerous|title=Navarro's Trade Views 'Misguided', 'Dangerous'|date=December 23, 2016|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref> In a ''Wall Street Journal'' op-ed defending his views, Navarro stated, \"If we are able to reduce our trade deficits through tough, smart negotiations, we should be able to increase our growth.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-white-house-worries-about-trade-deficits-1488751930|title=Why the White House Worries About Trade Deficits|last=Navarro|first=Peter|date=March 5, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 12, 2017|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Harvard University economics professor [[Greg Mankiw|Gregory Mankiw]] has said that Navarro's views on the trade deficit are based on the kind of mistakes that \"even a freshman at the end of ec 10 knows.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gregmankiw.blogspot.com/2016/09/trumponomics.html|title=Greg Mankiw's Blog: Trumponomics|last=|first=|date=|website=gregmankiw.blogspot.com|language=en|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/meet-mr-death-by-china-trumps-inside-man-on-trade/2017/02/17/164d7458-ea25-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html|title=Meet Mr. 'Death by China,' Trump's inside man on trade|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> Tufts University professor [[Daniel W. Drezner]] said about Navarro's op-ed, \"as someone who's written on this topic I could not for the life of me understand his reasoning\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2017/03/09/why-the-trump-administration-hates-multilateral-trade-agreements-the-most/|title=Perspective {{!}} Why the Trump administration hates multilateral trade agreements the most|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> According to [[Tyler Cowen]], \"close to no one\" in the economics profession agrees with Navarro's idea that a trade deficit is bad in and of itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208134200/http://www.chronicle.com/article/What-You-Should-Know-About-the/238590|archivedate=2016-12-08|title=What You Should Know About the Professor Who Has Trump's Ear on the Economy |publisher= The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 8, 2016|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref> Nobel laureate [[Angus Deaton]] described Navarro's attitude on trade deficits as \"an old-fashioned mercantilist position.\"<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n''[[The Economist]]'' magazine has described Navarro's views on the trade deficit as \"dodgy economics\",<ref name=\":0\" /> while the ''Financial Times'' has described them as \"poor economics\".<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/eea50292-0331-11e7-aa5b-6bb07f5c8e12|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> Economists Noah Smith,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-12-28/trump-s-trade-chief-peter-navarro-makes-a-rookie-mistake|title=Trump's Trade Chief Makes a Rookie Mistake|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=December 28, 2016|work=Bloomberg View|access-date=March 7, 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Sumner]], [[Olivier Blanchard]],<ref name=\":10\" /> and Phil Levy<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/phillevy/2017/03/06/white-house-whiffs-on-trade-deficit-defense/#7aea21f06b6c|title=White House Whiffs On Trade Deficit Defense|last=Levy |first=Phil|work=Forbes|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> have also criticized Navarro's views on the trade deficit. Dan Ikenson, director of the [[Cato Institute]]'s Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies goes so far as to call Navarro a \"charlatan\" and says that \"99.9 per cent of respectable economists would eschew\" what he says: \"He says imports deduct from output, and he calls that accounting identity the 'economic growth formula'. He thinks that for every dollar we import, our GDP is reduced by a dollar. I don't know how he got his PhD at Harvard.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=The purge of April: Trump's new advisers pour on the gas |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/the-purge-of-april-trump-s-new-advisers-pour-on-the-gas-1.4705201 |website=www.cbc.ca |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to Trans-Pacific Partnership ===\nNavarro opposes the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/238473-parsing-the-trans-pacific-partnership-agreement|title=Parsing the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=April 13, 2015|work=The Hill|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In an April 2015 op-ed, Navarro said, \"To woo us, their spinmeisters boast the TPP will spur American exports to stimulate sorely needed economic growth. In truth, the American economy will suffer severely. This is because the TPP will hammer two main drivers of economic growth\u2014domestic investment and 'net exports.'\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Navarro said in March 2017 that TPP \"would have been a \"death knell\" to America's auto and vehicle parts industry that we \"urgently need to bring back to full life.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> ''Politico''<nowiki/>'s Jacob Heilbrunn and ''the'' ''Economist'' argue that there may be a disconnect between Navarro's policy on China and his opposition to the TPP, as scuttling the TPP will strengthen China's hand.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Library resources box|about=no|by=yes}}\n\n* ''Crouching Tiger: What China's Militarism Means for the World'' (2015)\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BBe2wpZqN0s Episode 1: Will There Be War With China?]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUA_wh88fYc Episode 2: The World At the Tip of a Chinese Spear]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odiv79hZhB4 Episode 3: The Wild Card of North Korea]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HEjlcmfNt3Y Episode 4: The Unsinkable Aircraft Carrier of Taiwan]\n** [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1csrTOxJ8JM Episode 5: Will There Be War Between China and Japan?]\n* ''[[Death by China (book)|Death by China: Confronting the Dragon \u2013 A Global Call to Action]]'' (2011)\n* ''Seeds of Destruction'' (with [[Glenn Hubbard (economist)|Glenn Hubbard]]) (2010)\n* ''Always a Winner: Finding Your Competitive Advantage in an Up and Down Economy'' (2009)\n* ''The Well-Timed Strategy: Managing the Business Cycle for Competitive Advantage'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Coming China Wars]]'' (2006)\n* ''What the Best MBAs Know'' (2005)\n* ''Principles of Economics: Business, Banking, Finance, and Your Everyday Life'' (2005)\n* ''When the Market Moves, Will You Be Ready?'' (2003)\n* ''If It's Raining in Brazil, Buy Starbucks''<ref name=ISBN /> (2001)\n* ''Bill Clinton's Agenda for America'' (1993)\n* ''Job Opportunities Under Clinton/Gore'' (with Craig Adams) (1993)\n* ''The Policy Game'' (1984)\n* ''The Dimming of America: The Real Costs of Electric Utility Regulation'' (1984)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"PMSB-Awards\">{{cite web|title=Teaching Awards|url=http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|publisher=The Paul Merage School of Business|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826230801/http://merage.uci.edu/Faculty/CourseDescriptions/TeachingAwards.aspx|archivedate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BP-CA49\">{{cite web|title=California's 49th Congressional District Elections|url=https://ballotpedia.org/California%27s_49th_C