{"title_page": "Nai (caste)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Nai\n| population = \n| popplace = Almost all the states and union territories of India\n| languages = {{hlist|[[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]|[[Hindi]]|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|[[Kannada language|Kannada]]|[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]}}\n| rels = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\nThe '''Nai''' (also known as '''Nayee''', '''Nyayee '''and as '''Valand''' in [[Gujarat]]) is a [[Caste system in India|caste]] originating in India.<ref name=PoIp1067>{{cite book |title=People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=XLII |editor1-first=A. |editor1-last=Hasan |editor2-first=J. C. |editor2-last=Das |page=1067}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1415\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Three edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 1415\u20131418</ref> The members were traditionally occupied as [[barber]]s.\n\n==Distribution==\nIn the state of [[Gujarat]], the Nais are referred by the name [[Nai]]. The Valand surname refer by Kathiya vadi Gujarati who have occupation of barber valand also have several territorial divisions, such as the, [[Gohil]], and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ''ataks'', the main ones being the [[Parmar]] and Rathod. The Valand are [[endogamy|endogamous]] and practice clan [[exogamy]]. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas.\n\nThe Nai community is listed as an [[Other Backward Class]] in various regions of India. These include:\n*[[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/andhrapradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Assam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/assam.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Bihar]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/bihar.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Bihar |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Chandigarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/chandigarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Chhattisgarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/Chhattisgarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Dadra and Nagar Haveli]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/dadarandnagarhaveli.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Daman and Diu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/damananddiu.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Delhi]] [[National Capital Region (India)|NCR]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/delhi.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Delhi |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/goa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/gujarat.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Gujarat |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Haryana]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/haryana.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Haryana |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Himachal Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/himachalpradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\"/>\n*[[Jharkhand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/jharkhand.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Karnataka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/karnataka.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/madhyapradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Madhya Pradesh |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Maharashtra]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/maharashtra.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Maharashtra |page=4 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Odisha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/orrisa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Puducherry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/puducherry.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/punjab.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Punjab |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Rajasthan]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/rajasthan.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Rajasthan |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Tripura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tripura.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttarakhand|Uttaranchal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttaranchal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Uttar Pradesh |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[West Bengal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Clans and divisions of the Valand==\n\nThe Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the Soratia, Halai, Gohil, and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ataks, the main ones being the Solanki, Rathore,  Parmar and Padaliya . The Valand are endogamous and practice clan exogamy. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas. The community are still essentially involved in the barbering trade, with a few rural Valand have taken up agriculture. A few were practitioners of [[Ayurvedic]]  medicine.<ref name=\"autogenerated1415\"/>{{full citation needed|date=June 2016}}{{qn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nai}}\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Barber castes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Nai\n| population = \n| popplace = Almost all the states and union territories of India\n| languages = {{hlist|[[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]|[[Hindi]]|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|[[Kannada language|Kannada]]|[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]}}\n| rels = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\nThe '''Nai''' (also known as '''Nayee''', '''Nyayee '''and as '''Valand''' in [[Gujarat]]) is a [[Caste system in India|caste]] originating in India.<ref name=PoIp1067>{{cite book |title=People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=XLII |editor1-first=A. |editor1-last=Hasan |editor2-first=J. C. |editor2-last=Das |page=1067}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1415\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Three edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 1415\u20131418</ref> The members were traditionally occupied as [[barber]]s.\n\n==Distribution==\nIn the state of [[Gujarat]], the Nais are referred by the name [[Nai]],[[Nyayee]] ,[[Sharma]], [[vaid]] [[Vaidya]] etc in Uttar Gujarat. The Valand surname refer by Kathiya vadi Gujarati who have occupation of barber valand also have several territorial divisions, such as the, [[Gohil]], and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ''ataks'', the main ones being the [[Parmar]] and Rathod. The Valand are [[endogamy|endogamous]] and practice clan [[exogamy]]. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas.{{Page needed|date=January 2015}}{{Qn|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe Nai community is listed as an [[Other Backward Class]] in various regions of India. These include:\n*[[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/andhrapradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Assam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/assam.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Bihar]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/bihar.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Bihar |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Chandigarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/chandigarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Chhattisgarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/Chhattisgarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Dadra and Nagar Haveli]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/dadarandnagarhaveli.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Daman and Diu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/damananddiu.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Delhi]] [[National Capital Region (India)|NCR]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/delhi.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Delhi |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/goa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/gujarat.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Gujarat |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Haryana]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/haryana.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Haryana |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Himachal Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/himachalpradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\"/>\n*[[Jharkhand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/jharkhand.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Karnataka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/karnataka.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/madhyapradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Madhya Pradesh |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Maharashtra]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/maharashtra.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Maharashtra |page=4 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Odisha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/orrisa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Puducherry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/puducherry.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/punjab.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Punjab |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Rajasthan]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/rajasthan.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Rajasthan |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Tripura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tripura.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttarakhand|Uttaranchal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttaranchal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Uttar Pradesh |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[West Bengal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Clans and divisions of the Valand==\n\nThe Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the Soratia, Halai, Gohil, and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ataks, the main ones being the Solanki, Rathore,  Parmar and Padaliya . The Valand are endogamous and practice clan exogamy. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas. The community are still essentially involved in the barbering trade, with a few rural Valand have taken up agriculture. A few were practitioners of [[Ayurvedic]]  medicine.<ref name=\"autogenerated1415\"/>{{full citation needed|date=June 2016}}{{qn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nai}}\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Barber castes]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unreferenced", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nai_(caste)"}
{"title_page": "Tornquist Sea", "text_new": "{{short description|A sea between the palaeocontinents Avalonia and Baltica about 600 to 450 million years ago}}\nThe '''Tornquist Sea''' or '''Tornquist Ocean''' was a sea located between the palaeocontinents [[Avalonia]] and [[Baltica]] about {{Mya|600|450}}.  The remains of the sea today form a suture stretching across northern Europe ([[Tornquist Zone]]).\n\n==Geologic evolution==\n{{Image label begin|image=Tectonic map Europe.jpg|width=350|float=right|alt=Tectonic map of Europe}}\n{{Image label|x=0.06|y=1.02|scale=350|text=<small>LEGEND Tectonic framework map of Europe</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.08|y=1.06|scale=350|text=<small>Baltica</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.08|y=1.1|scale=350|text=<small>Caledonian (Laurentia)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.08|y=1.14|scale=350|text=<small>Caledonian (Baltica)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.59|y=1.06|scale=350|text=<small>Avalonia</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.59|y=1.1|scale=350|text=<small>Hercynian</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.59|y=1.14|scale=350|text=<small>Alpine</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.46|y=0.65|scale=350|text=<small>Alps</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.66|y=0.61|scale=350|text=<small>Carpathians</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.8|y=0.54|scale=350|text=<small>Ukrainian shield</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.24|y=0.71|scale=350|text=<small>Pyrenees</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.46|y=0.8|scale=350|text=<small>Apennines</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.59|y=0.73|scale=350|text=<small>Dinarides</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.06|y=0.96|scale=350|text=<small>Atlas</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.6|y=0.26|scale=350|text=<small>Baltic shield</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.27|y=0.47|scale=350|text=<small>London-Brabant massif</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.1|y=0.84|scale=350|text=<small>Cordillera Betica</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.06|y=1.22|scale=350|text=<small>Tectonic map of Europe; the Teisseyre-Tornquist Zone is located between the [[London-Brabant Massif]] (=Eastern Avalonia) and the [[Baltic Shield]].  The Tornquist Fan stretches across Denmark.</small>}}\n{{Image label end}}\nIt probably formed at the same time (c. 600 Ma) as the [[Iapetus Ocean]]. [[Gondwana]], including Avalonia until [[Early Ordovician]], was separate from Baltica throughout the [[Cambrian]]. It probably closed during the [[Late Ordovician]] at the time of the [[Shelveian Orogeny]] of western England.<ref name=\"McKerrow-etal\">{{Harvnb|McKerrow|Mac Niocaill|Ahlberg|Clayton|2000|p=12}}</ref>\n\nThere are faunal, palaeomagnetic, palaeogeographic, and [[apparent polar wander]] path evidence for the timing of closure for Eastern Avalonia (England, Wales and southern Ireland) and Baltica.<ref>{{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Van der Voo|Trench|1993|loc=Summary}}; {{Harvnb|Torsvik|Rehnstr\u00f6m|2003|loc=8. Avalonia and Baltica convergence and the tale of K-bentonites, pp. 77\u201380}}.  Torsvik et al. 1993 proposed a \"pre-[[Wenlock (Silurian)|Wenlock]] (Early Silurian) collision\" but (e.g.) Torsvik & Rehnstr\u00f6m 2003 modified the timing to Late Ordovician.</ref>\n\nThe Baltica-Avalonia collision also resulted in that the [[Rheic Ocean]] ceased to expand south of Avalonia around 450 Ma, in huge magmatism in Avalonia, gigantic ash fall in Baltica, and metamorphism in present-day northern Germany.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nance|Guti\u00e9rrez-Alonso|Keppie|Linnemann|2010|loc=3.2. Closure and collision, pp. 7\u20138}}</ref>\n\n==Present-day suture==\nThe suture resulting from closure of the Tornquist Sea may be seen in eastern England and the [[Lake District]] as an arc of igneous rocks belonging to the Ordovician. The volcanic series in eastern England, the [[Ardennes]] and the Northern [[Phyllite]] Belt originated between the Tornquist Sea and the [[Rheic Ocean]] during the Ordovician and [[Silurian]].<ref name=\"McKerrow-etal\" />\n\nWhere Baltica and Avalonia finally collided is now a [[Suture (geology)|suture]] known as the Teisseyre-Tornquist Line or Zone; named after its discoverer, Polish geologist [[Wawrzyniec Teisseyre]]<!--(1860-1939)--> and German geologist [[Alexander Tornquist]]<!--(1868-1944)-->.  This lineament still marks the transition between, on one hand, the East and North European Pre-Cambrian Craton and, on the other hand, the West European and Mediterranean Palaeozoic Orogenes.  It is part of a wider deformation zone running across Europe, from the British Isles to the Black Sea, known as the [[Trans-European Suture Zone]] (TESZ).<ref>{{Harvnb|Teisseyre|Teisseyre|2002|p=841}}; Tornquist erroneously identified as a \"Swedish magnetologist\"</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Grad|Guterch|Polkowska-Purys|2005}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = Grad | first1 = M.\n | last2 = Guterch | first2 = A.\n | last3 = Polkowska-Purys | first3 = A.\n | title = Crustal structure of the Trans-European Suture Zone in Central Poland\u2014 reinterpretation of the LT-2, LT-4 and LT-5 deep seismic sounding profiles\n | year = 2005 | journal = Geological Quarterly | volume = 49 | issue = 3 | pages = 243\u2013252\n | url = http://www.pgi.gov.pl/images/stories/przeglad/pdf/gq_49_3_p243.pdf | access-date = 22 November 2015\n | ref = harv}}<!-- {{Harvnb|Grad|Guterch|Polkowska-Purys|2005}} -->\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = McKerrow | first1 = W. S.\n | last2 = Mac Niocaill | first2 = C.\n | last3 = Ahlberg | first3 = P. E.\n | last4 = Clayton | first4 = G.\n | last5 = Cleal | first5 = C. J.\n | last6 = Eagar | first6 = R. M. C.\n | title = The late Palaeozoic relations between Gondwana and Laurussia\n | year = 2000 | journal = Geological Society, London, Special Publications | volume = 179 | issue = 1 | pages = 9\u201320\n | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232237515 | access-date = 22 November 2015\n | doi = 10.1144/GSL.SP.2000.179.01.03 | ref = harv| bibcode = 2000GSLSP.179....9M}}<!-- {{Harvnb|McKerrow|Mac Niocaill|Ahlberg|Clayton|2000}} -->\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = Nance | first1 = R. D.\n | last2 = Guti\u00e9rrez-Alonso | first2 = G.\n | last3 = Keppie | first3 = J. D.\n | last4 = Linnemann | first4 = U.\n | last5 = Murphy | first5 = J. B.\n | last6 = Quesada | first6 = C.\n | last7 = Strachan | first7 = R. A.\n | last8 = Woodcock | first8 = N. H.\n | title = Evolution of the Rheic ocean\n | year = 2010 | journal = Gondwana Research | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 194\u2013222\n | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223716583 | access-date = 22 November 2015\n | doi = 10.1016/j.gr.2009.08.001 | ref = harv| bibcode = 2010GondR..17..194N}}<!-- {{Harvnb|Nance|Guti\u00e9rrez-Alonso|Keppie|Linnemann|2010}} -->\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = Teisseyre | first1 = R.\n | last2 = Teisseyre | first2 = B.\n | title = Wawrzyniec Karol de Teisseyre: A Pioneer in the Study of \"Cryptotectonics\"\n | year = 2002 | journal = Eos | volume = 83 | issue = 47 | pages = 541\u2013546\n | ref = harv | doi=10.1029/2002EO000370| bibcode = 2002EOSTr..83..541T}}<!-- {{Harvnb|Teisseyre|Teisseyre|2002}} -->\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = Torsvik | first1 = T. H.\n | last2 = Smethurst | first2 = M. A.\n | last3 = Van der Voo | first3 = R.\n | last4 = Trench | first4 = A.\n | last5 = Abrahamsen | first5 = N.\n | last6 = Halvorsen | first6 = E.\n | title = Baltica. A synopsis of Vendian-Permian palaeomagnetic data and their palaeotectonic implications\n | year = 1993 | journal = Earth-Science Reviews | volume = 33 | issue = 2 | pages = 133\u2013152\n | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227932193 | access-date = 22 November 2015\n | ref = harv | doi=10.1016/0012-8252(92)90023-m| bibcode = 1992ESRv...33..133T| hdl = 2027.42/29743\n }}<!-- {{Harvnb|Torsvik|Smethurst|Van der Voo|Trench|1993}} -->\n* {{Cite journal\n | last1 = Torsvik | first1 = T. H.\n | last2 = Rehnstr\u00f6m | first2 = E. F.\n | title = The Tornquist Sea and Baltica\u2013Avalonia docking\n | year = 2003 | journal = Tectonophysics | volume = 362 | issue = 1 | pages = 67\u201382\n | url = 